<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Make Apology If Proved Wrong in Clashes: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda would sincerely
apologize to Uganda if the final report on the recent Kisangani
clashes between the two countries' troops proves that Rwandan
troops shot first.
</P>
<P>
Charles Murigande, secretary-general of Rwanda's ruling
Patriotic Front, made the remarks at a meeting with Ugandan
Parliament Speaker Francis Ayume here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The final report would pick out the culprit. If Rwandan
soldiers shot the first shot, Kigali should apologize to Kampala
for death of Ugandan soldiers," Murigande said when paying a
courtesy call to Ayume.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries should be brothers instead of allies and
they should strengthen relations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan top legislator also called for the two countries
to iron out their differences and work for national reconciliation
and political dialogue on the basis of mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
In the August 14-17 armed clashes between the two countries'
troops in Kisangani, the third largest city in the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC), both parties sustained heavy losses.
Uganda lost a total of 38 servicemen and Rwanda reportedly lost
more.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, both supporting the rebels trying to topple
DRC President Laurent Kabila, accused each other of inciting the
fighting in Kisangani and their bilateral relations plummeted to
the rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
After the clashes, leaders of the two neighbor countries
agreed to establish a joint inquiry team to look into the cause of
the shoot-out. However, when the report came out, Uganda rejected
it saying it was biased and inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
Uganda then set up a fresh probe team headed by State Minister
for Defense Steven Kavuma to dig deeper into the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
