<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Launches Operation Against PKK in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkey Wednesday launched a
cross-border military operation against rebels of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in northern Iraq, the local NTV
reported Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The 5,000-strong Turkish security forces had entered 10
kilometers deep into northern Iraq and killed at least 16 PKK
rebels there, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has set up many camps to shelter thousands of its
militants based in northern Iraq since the Gulf War in 1991. It
often launches raids on Turkey's military and civilian targets
from the Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
The imprisoned PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan last Wednesday
called on a PKK group to surrender to the Turkish security forces
in order to show their sincerity for peace.
</P>
<P>
One day later, Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said that
"the surrender of armed militants will be evaluated as a positive
development."
</P>
<P>
"We have been encouraging such a development for years. As you
know, the Repentance Law has been approved by the parliament. In
the framework of Turkish justice, militants who hand over their
arms will be shown maximum tolerance."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that in the next couple of days, either on
Turkey's southern border or on its border with Iran, some PKK
members would turn themselves in to the government.
</P>
<P>
Anatolia news agency reported on Wednesday that about 30 PKK
militants raided a police vehicle in Tatvan town of Bitlis
province Tuesday night, wounding one policeman.
</P>
<P>
In the counter-attack, the Turkish security forces killed
three PKK rebels in the region.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts between the PKK
and the government troops have claimed over 37,000 lives since
then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
