<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Nyerere "Quite Good" in London Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Former Tanzanian President
Julius Nyerere, who is currently in a hospital here for leukaemia,
is in quite good condition, a Tanzanian official here said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"His condition is not excellent, but he is quite good now," an
official from the Tanzanian High Commission in London told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the former president "has not left the
hospital yet."
</P>
<P>
Nyerere has been a major figure in post-colonial Africa. He was
admitted to St Thomas's Hospital in London on Friday, in what the
East African country's President Benjamin Mkapa described as a
"very critical condition."
</P>
<P>
He led the then Tanganyika to independence from Britain in
1961. After retiring as president in 1985, he kept on playing an
advisory role in both Tanzanian politics and African affairs.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere earned international respect for his integrity and
intellect and has for the past four years led regional efforts to
bring peace to Burundi, which borders Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Doctors diagnosed Nyerere as suffering from a chronic form of
leukaemia in August, 1998. But at that time doctors said he did
not need immediate medical attention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
