<HEADLINE> Lebanon Approves Operations of Six New Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government
Wednesday night approved grant of licenses to two TV and four
radio stations, raising the number of the country's TV and radio
stations to eight and 19 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Anwar Khalil announced after the weekly
regular cabinet session that all six licenses have been approved
by the state-run Central Media Council, which oversees the
operations of the TV and radio stations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The two TV stations granted license are ICN and UTV, both were
shut down during the reign of former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri,
who reduced the number of functioning radios in Lebanon from 150
to 15 and TV networks to six.
</P>
<P>
The new radio stations include two religious channels,
Christian Hallelujah and Muslim Nida Al Maarifah, which would be
run by the Islamic Charity Organization.
</P>
<P>
The other two are Al-Nour run by the country's leading
anti-Israel military group Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the
Voice of the Nation run by a statesman Saeb Salam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
