<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ostrich Production Keeps Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's ostrich production
levels have been consistent despite the dropout by half of its
producers in 1998, the Commercial Ostrich Producers Association of
Zimbabwe said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chris Bradshaw, managing director of the association, said
production levels remain at 15,000 birds a year although there are
now only 40 producers in the country compared with 100 producers
in 1998 when ostrich production was at its peak.
</P>
<P>
"There has been positive development with the remaining
producers expanding production. Prices have also gone up by
about 35 percent and a single bird now costs around 10,000
Zimbabwean dollars (264 U.S. dollars), 3,000 Zimbabwean dollars
(78.9 U.S. dollars) more than last year," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been no change to live bird exports which had
 witnessed a lull due to the glut which led to the collapse of
world markets.
</P>
<P>
"In the past six months we have exported exclusive top quality
leather goods to Australia, Canada, United States and Europe," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The total number of ostrich in the country is estimated to be
between 50, 000 and 60,000.
</P>
<P>
The country exports 90 percent of the ostrich meat to the
European Union and Mauritius while the rest of the meat is
consumed locally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
