<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's government and opposition have recently
launched a new cycle of war of words against each other, plunging
the civil war-stricken country into a new political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The storm was triggered by Post and Telecommunications
Minister Issam Naaman, a close ally of Prime Minister Salim Hoss,
who accused former premier and Hoss's long-time rival Rafik Hariri
of handing out financial aid to students in an attempt to secure
votes in next year's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's foundation is reportedly paying 200 U.S. dollars for
each needy student in Beirut to meet their spiraling tuition
fees as the new scholastic year begins. (BC-Lebanon-Political War)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Wednesday released 276 Iraqi prisoner of war
(POWs) unilaterally, the official Iranian news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA), the
decision to free the Iraqis was made on the occasion of the 100th
birth anniversary of the late Iranian spiritual leader Imam
Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Brigadier Mohammad Balar, the spokesman and head of
the Public Relations and Publicity Department of POWs Commissions,
said the Iraqis will be released in the presence of a red cross
representative. (BC-Iran-Iraq-POWs)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- German businessman Helmut Hofer has finally eschewed
death sentence as an Iranian court dropped the adultery charge
against him at a trial Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Head of a Tehran public court, Yusef Musavi, said at the
closed-door trial that the adultery charge against Hofer which
carries death sentence in Iran was not proved.
</P>
<P>
He concluded that "Hofer's sentence is not death."
(BC-Iran-Germany-Trial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will ring in the new millennium with a dazzling
overnight opera in the desert before the three Great Pyramids on
the Giza Plateau, the country's minister of culture said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented audiovisual event will turn the pyramids of
Cheops, Khefren and Mykerinos and the surrounding desert into a
sprawling laser-lit stage for 1,000 performers and artists, Farouk
Hosni said.
</P>
<P>
It will begin at sunset on New Year's Eve and end at dawn on
the first day of the third millennium, and will evoke the ancient
and modern art forms of the West and the East.
(BC-Egypt-Millennium-Celebrations) 
</P>
</TEXT>
