<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-29 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Slams Israel's Objection to U.N. Role in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa on Wednesday dismissed as rubbish his Israeli counterpart
David Levy's recent statements that intervention by the United
Nations in the Mideast peace process could hamstring the drive.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a cabinet meeting, Moussa validated
U.N. intervention in the Mideast peace march as a legitimate move
to address and face Israeli violations of the relevant resolutions
on Mideast issues adopted by the world organization.
</P>
<P>
If Israel halted settlement activities in the Arab occupied
territories, there would be no need to ask the U.N. to pass a
resolution to denounce and demand a halt of the Israeli practices,
Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
A possible U.N. resolution would be mandatory for the
international community to deal with Israel's violation of the
principles of peace, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and other Arab countries have sought to pass a
resolution by the U.N. General Assembly calling for Israel's
ending of settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moussa reiterated Egypt's stance that the resumption
of the multilateral talks should follow the re-start of the
negotiations between Syria and Lebanon on one side and Israel
on the other.
</P>
<P>
Should the talks on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks resume,
besides the Palestinian track, "then there would be no problem"
concerning the multilateral talks, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said on Sunday that the multilateral peace talks will
not be resumed before Israel re-starts negotiations with Syria and
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which kicked off in 1992, came to a halt in 1996
when former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took
office. The talks covered issues including disarmament, water,
Palestinian refugees, the environment and economic cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
