<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants Australia to Scale Down Troops in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia on Wednesday
advocated more ASEAN participation in peace-keeping in East Timor
and a scale-down of Australian troops in the U.N.-authorized
multi-national force (MNF) in the territory.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad made the statement at a press
conference, saying that he also voiced this view to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan during a meeting Wednesday before
addressing the 54th Session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"I did raise this matter of Australia's heavy-handed dealing
with the problem in East Timor, and I feel that it is necessary
that Australia scale down its forces there, and allow ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) rather to take
peace-keeping there," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said a lot of people in the region "feel threatened"
because of "the too much participation on the part of big western
countries" in the mission.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN countries are taking initiatives in solving the East
Timor issue but "it doesn't mean that we should send a big
military force or to carry out a military operation there", he
said. "
</P>
<P>
He said Annan told him that for the moment there is a need for
Australia to send a big force because other countries have not
sent their forces there.
</P>
<P>
"Should there be more peace-keeping troops from other
countries, it will be necessary to scale down Australia's
participation," Mahathir quoted Annan as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council on September 15 passed a resolution
to establish the MNF to restore peace and security in East Timor
which is in the transitional period toward independence following
the August 30 ballot.
</P>
<P>
Australia led the move by sending an initial 1,200 troops with
an objective of dispatching a maximum of 4,500, joining the MNF
which is expected to finally number 8,000. Troops contributed by a
number of countries have reached 3,200. 
</P>
</TEXT>
