<HEADLINE> Southern African International Dialogue to Open in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen heads of state and
government from Sub-Sahara Africa and Malaysia will attend the
third Southern African International Dialogue from October 3 to 6
at the well-known Victoria Falls, a Zimbabwean official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Misheck Sibanda, principal secretary in the Office of the
President and Cabinet, said the conference will also be attended
by about 400 other participants from countries of Africa, Asia,
Europe as well as the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said the conference whose theme is "Economic Empowerment
through Smart Partnership" will seek to develop partnerships to
propel economic empowerment in the southern and eastern African
region.
</P>
<P>
Focus will also be on the economic crisis within the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) region, which is plagued by
unemployment, poverty, spiraling inflation and the HIV/AIDS
pandemic, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the light of these challenges there is the imperative to
develop new ways of doing business. Interaction through smart
partnership provides the best solution to the creation of wealth
that is accompanied by the empowerment of all the social
partners," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the conference will be a follow-up to the Langkawi
International Dialogue held in Malaysia to develop the partnership
nationally, regionally and internationally.
</P>
<P>
"Besides the traditional media firing questions to heads of
governments, the government leaders will have the opportunity to
turn the tables around - - finding out how the media is
contributing to the empowerment process," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
