<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Media Urged to Take Common Stands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Newspapers, broadcasters
and other media of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) countries
were urged Wednesday to take concerted action toward any exterior
"insult or defamation."
</P>
<P>
A common stance must be adopted in the event of any member of
the GCC states facing insult or defamation either from media
institutions or individuals, stressed ministers of information
and culture of the six GCC countries after winding up a two-day
meeting in Al Ain, the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
Chaired by the UAE Minister of Information and Culture Sheikh
Abdullah Bin Zayed Al Nahyan, the meeting called for collective
commitment to resolutions of the GCC Supreme Council, including
those related to the development of joint media activities and
improvement of exterior information work.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed that exterior information work must be
improved to build bridges of cooperation with the international
media institutions.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to proposals for organizing GCC cultural
weeks abroad, the first of which would be held in Brussels,
Belgium, next year.
</P>
<P>
The GCC is a regional political and economic alliance
comprising the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and
Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
