<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Attaches Importance to Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
attached great importance to rural electrification as a way to
increase the life quality and incomes of the rural people who
constitute more than 80 percent of the country's 22 million
people.
</P>
<P>
Syda Bbumba, minister of Energy and Mineral Development, made
the remarks Wednesday at the ground breaking ceremony of a rural
electrification project in Mukono district, 30 kilometers east of
the capital Kampala, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
She regretted that the power consumption in rural areas is the
lowest in the region although Uganda has immense resources for the
generation of cheap hydro-power.
</P>
<P>
At present, she said, less than one percent of the country's
rural population has access to power.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has been committed to increasing rural
power access to about 10 percent of the rural population by the
year 2010, she said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the Uganda Electricity Board,
about five percent of the population has access to power and more
than 80 percent of these people are in the three major cities of
Kampala, Entebbe and Jinja.  
</P>
</TEXT>
