<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Usher in New Millennium With Dazzling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will ring in the new
millennium with a dazzling overnight opera in the desert before
the three Great Pyramids on the Giza Plateau, the country's
minister of culture said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented audiovisual event will turn the pyramids of
Cheops, Khefren and Mykerinos and the surrounding desert into a
sprawling laser-lit stage for 1,000 performers and artists, Farouk
Hosni said.
</P>
<P>
It will begin at sunset on New Year's Eve and end at dawn on
the first day of the third millennium, and will evoke the ancient
and modern art forms of the West and the East.
</P>
<P>
The opera, composed and directed by French recording artist
Jean Michel Jarre, is titled The Twelve Dreams of the Sun. It will
depict the pharaonic belief that after setting on the western
horizon, the sun travels in a boat through the dark underworld and
passes through 12 gates in 12 hours to be born again, strong and
youthful.
</P>
<P>
It will feature fireworks, laser lights projecting images on
the Pyramids and lighting effects "that will be seen for the first
time in the world," Hosni told a press conference that was also
addressed by Jarre.
</P>
<P>
At the stroke of midnight, a golden pyramid about 9 meters high
will be placed atop the missing peak of the Great Pyramid of
Cheops, flooding the surrounding area with golden rays to signal
the birth of the first day of 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Culture Ministry will foot the 9.5 million U.S. dollars
bill for the show. "But a major budget was already paid for by the
pharaohs thousands of years ago when they built the pyramids," he
said.
</P>
<P>
For Jarre, who has organized spectacular outdoor performances
in Houston, Beijing, London, Paris and Moscow, it will be his
biggest project ever, using a 20,000-square-meter stage.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 people are expected to attend the show. Sixty
countries have bought televising rights.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian army will open its airport in the Western Desert
for special flights that will bring foreign spectators on December
31 and fly them back on January 1. The golden pyramid, made of a
yet-undecided light metal, will be removed after the show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
