<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel on Reconciliation with Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the 54th session of the
United Nations General Assembly, Israel's Deputy Prime Minister
and Minister of Foreign Affairs David Levy said normalization
must not be viewed as a one-side gesture, it is not in the
service of one particular party, and it is in the interest of
all the nations of the region.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to renew the multilateral tracks already this year.
There is a need for close cooperation in the regional
multilateral projects. This region has tremendous potential. In
order to fully realize this potential, we must establish a
mechanism of true cooperation among the states of the region.
This cooperation would clearly be to the benefit of all of us in
the region," Levy said.
</P>
<P>
"The working groups of the multilateral tracks undertook
different assignments of primary importance. Unfortunately,
their activities are frozen due to irrelevant reasons. This is
the time to resurrect them. Any delay or imposed conditions is
liable to undermine the peace process and delay the aid package
so essential to the peoples of the region," said he.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt and Jordan were our first partners in breaking the
walls of enmity and in warming of relations in our region.
Improving our relations with Egypt, as well as renewing the
multilateral tracks, are essential to further the common
objectives of the nations in our region," Levy went to say.
</P>
<P>
"The relations between Israel and Jordan are an example of
appropriate and favorable relations between neighboring
countries. We intend to strengthen and broaden the relations
between the two nations, in the economic, social and political
realms," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
