<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Syrian Foreign Minister on Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Wednesday met with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara to discuss ways for resumption of long-stalled peace
negotiations between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The president is prepared to be engaged and try to be
helpful to try to provide a catalyst for getting the talks
resumed," White House National Security Council spokesman Mike
Hammer told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting was a continuation of Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's efforts last week to insert some momentum
into the deadlock over the Syrian-Israeli talks, which was
suspended in 1996 after Israel's Labor Party lost to the Likud
Group in the May elections.
</P>
<P>
Syria said the then Israeli Labor government Israel secretly
promised before the 1996 elections that Israel would return the
Golan Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967 Six-Day war. But
Likud leader Benjamin Netanyahu after assuming power rejected
the commitment by the former Labor government, and the talks
thus broke down.
</P>
<P>
Ehud Barak, Israel's Labor leader, defeated Netanyahu in the
May elections this year and promised to make "painful
compromise" for the revival of the negotiations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Hammer said Clinton believed "there's a real opportunity to
move on the Syrian track."
</P>
<P>
"We have been working hard with both Israel and Syria to find
a way for them to resume discussions ... Clearly we wouldn't be
having this meeting if we didn't think there was some chance of
success," Hammer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Wednesday convened an open session on Africa in order to
view the progress in curbing conflicts and promoting development
on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is held after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
presented a report, saying that African nations have never been
better placed than now to benefit from outside involvement and
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from a total of 48 countries are scheduled to
take the floor at the open meeting, airing their viewpoints on how
to aid Africa at the turn of century.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
Salim Ahamed Salim is the first to speak at the meeting, he spoke
of the cooperation between his organization and the United Nations
in African affairs.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his report, painted a mixed picture of Africa today,
saying "Africa, today, on the eve of the new millennium, reveals a
remarkable combination of accomplishments and unresolved problems,
of opportunities seized and chances missed."
</P>
<P>
"The birth of so many new states in Africa this century, with
all the attendant euphoria and high expectations, has been quickly
followed by disillusionment and disappointment," he said.
</P>
<P>
In April last year, Annan presented a report on Africa to both
the General Assembly and the Security Council, shedding light on
the causes of conflict and the promotion of durable peace and
sustainable development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The report "attracted wide interest and attention and has been
discussed and analysed in various forums, within and outside the
United Nations systems," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a very encouraging response to the report from
Governments, research and academic institutions, civil society
groups, non-governmental organizations and individuals, many of
whom have used the debate surrounding the report as an opportunity
to contribute to the search for peace and development in Africa,"
he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
