<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Paints Mixed Picture of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday painted a mixed picture of Africa today, saying
that Africa is characterized by "a combination of accomplishments
and unresolved problems, of opportunities seized and chances
missed."
</P>
<P>
Annan made the statement at the Security Council, which on
Wednesday morning convened an open session on Africa in order to
view the progress in curbing conflicts and promoting development
on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"There are places where Governments and rebel groups persist
in spending money on weapons they can ill afford for wars they
should not fight," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are places where whole economies have come to depend on
the perpetuation of war; where political power has been attained
by violent, undemocratic means; where poor governance deprives
people of basic needs; where silence about AIDS exacerbates the
epidemic; where corruption thwarts economic growth; where crushing
debt burdens, trade barriers and declining international aid make
it extremely hard for African nations to attract investment and
stave off further marginalization from the global economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Annan also reported progress in Africa, saying that
"many African nations are liberalizing trade and exchange
controls, privatizing moribund state industries, building up
communications infrastructure, and reforming their legal and
regulatory frameworks."
</P>
<P>
"Africa possesses land and labor resources that foreign
investors find attractive," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Africans are also taking charge of their political fortunes --
and they are willing to acknowledge past mistakes," he said. "A
majority of Africans now live under democratic systems."
</P>
<P>
The meeting came after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
presented a report, saying that African nations have never been
better placed than now to benefit from outside involvement and
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from a total of 48 countries are scheduled to
take the floor at the open meeting, airing their viewpoints on how
to aid Africa at the turn of century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
