<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Asks Iran for Help in Blast Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton has asked the Iranian government for cooperation in
finding the perpetrators of the 1996 bombing at a U.S. military
housing complex in Saudi Arabia, U.S. officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president sent his appeal in a letter last month, which was
carried by a senior White House official to Paris and given to an
emissary from the Persian Gulf country of Oman and then passed on
to Iran for President Mohammed Khatami, according to Wednesday's
edition of the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
Existence of the letter, the first direct message by Clinton
to the Iranian government, was first reported earlier this month
by Kuwait's al-Watan newspapers and was confirmed by State
Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been frustrated in the search for the
perpetrators of the truck bombing of the Khobar Towers apartment
complex on June 25, 1995. The blast killed 19 American
servicemen and injured more than 500 people.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Clinton held out the prospect of warmer
relations between Tehran and Washington. He said the United
States and Iran are two great civilizations and that cooperation
on combating terrorism is an important element for any great
power.
</P>
<P>
White House National Security Council spokesman David Leavy
said the United States has expressed an interest in better
relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to work on a road map for better relations with
Iran," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
