<HEADLINE> Pollution by Developed World Biggest Problem: UK's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, Britain, September 29 (Xinhua) -- British Deputy
Prime Minister John Prescott on Wednesday called the air pollution
by developed nations the biggest environment problem facing the
world.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest environmental challenge we face is the poisoning
of the earth's atmosphere by the industrialized countries," said
Prescott, who is also Britain's Secretary of State for the
Environment, Transport and the Regions.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Labor Party's annual conference on its third
day, Prescott said: "People see on TV the ice caps melting,
greater droughts, fiercer storms, rising seas, which threaten to
wipe out whole coastal communities."
</P>
<P>
"They know something is wrong and they want action," the deputy
prime minister noted, as he discussed the Labor Government's
policy on environment.
</P>
<P>
"That's why Britain led the world at the UN Climate Summit in
Kyodo, negotiating legal limits to the greenhouse gases that cause
global warming," Prescott claimed. "Because we have an obligation
to pass on our children a better world than the one we inherited."
</P>
<P>
He criticized politicians who "for too long have dodged
long-term responsibility for short-term expediency," saying the
Labor's policies "are decided not for tomorrow's newspapers, but
for tomorrow's children."  
</P>
</TEXT>
