<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Minister Urges Reduction of Debt, Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, Britain, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A senior
official of the British Government on Wednesday urged the
developed nations to write off the debt of and reduce the tariffs
against developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Byers, British Secretary for Trade and Industry, said
writing off debts of poor nations is not only "essential on
grounds of social justice," but also makes business sense allowing
those countries to revive their economies and to trade.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Labor Party's annual conference, Byers said the
British Government should "give a lead to the rest of the world"
on this issue. "Debts need to be cancelled now," he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, the British Government will have
written off debts of over 200 million U.S. dollars owed by poor
countries, and it has set a target of a further 500 million U.S.
dollars by the end of this Parliament or in three years, according
to Byers.
</P>
<P>
On world trade which he said is "paramount importance" at a
time of globalization, Byers called for stopping "farming
subsidies in the rich nations destroying the agriculture sector of
the poorer ones."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, "it's time we reduced tariffs
deliberately designed to block exports from developing countries."
</P>
<P>
In a globalized world, "protectionism anywhere is a threat to
prosperity everywhere," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the wider issues raised by the information revolution, he
noted, "a new class divide must not emerge between the information
'haves' and 'have nots'."  
</P>
</TEXT>
