<HEADLINE> Angolan Government Troops Attack UNITA Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fightings between the
Angolan government troops and the rebel militants are under way
around traditional rebel bases in the country's central plateau,
Angolan President Jose dos Santos said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos made the statement in a press conference after
meeting with the visiting President Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos said that in a bid to restore peace and stability,
"our troops are making necessary response" to the great tension in
provinces of Malange, Bie, Huambo and Uige, created by the rebels
of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
led by Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Heavy combats are under way within a radius of five to eight
kilometers of the center of Bailundo, one of the most important
bases for UNITA, sources said Wednesday. A spokesman for UNITA
has denied the loss of Bailundo "despite strong pressure".
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, over 250 government troops were
killed during the attack on Bailundo, a part of the seven-day
"general offensive" by the government troops on the cities of
Bailundo and Mungo in Huambo Province, Andulo and Nharea in Bie
Province, all strategic bases for UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rebels launched attacks on bridges and trucks to
impede the progress of the government troops.
</P>
<P>
During an attack on Monday on the town of Quindando in Uige
Province, the rebels killed 34 civilians and two policemen,
according to a local police source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
