<HEADLINE> Leukemia-Hit Nyerere Improves, but Develops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's founding
president Julius Nyerere, admitted in a London hospital for
leukemia last week, improved Wednesday but developed jaundice, an
official press release said.
</P>
<P>
Medical tests carried on Nyerere further indicated that the
hemoglobin count in his blood has steadily improved, a boost to
his immune system.
</P>
<P>
"He is able to express himself," Press Secretary to the
President Geoffrey Nkurlu said in the release.
</P>
<P>
"However, he has developed jaundice, a condition which has
been described as normal by doctors treating him," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa confirmed on Sunday at an
emergency news conference here that Nyerere is suffering from
chronic lymphocytic leukemia, or blood cancer and was admitted to
St Thomas Hospital last Thursday when he was not able to speak
with a bit consciousness.
</P>
<P>
The whole nation of Tanzania are praying for the recovery of
the 77- year-old founder of the country.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister for Regional Administration and Local
Governments Kingunge Ngombale-Mwiru was dispatched to London
Tuesday to join Nyerere's wife and two daughters to monitor his
condition.
</P>
<P>
Born in the town of Butiama, Tanganyika, in 1922, Nyerere led
the Tanganyika African National Union (TANU) to win independence
from British colonial rule in 1961.
</P>
<P>
He also united Tanganyika and Zanzibar as one republic in 1964
and became its first president until he retired in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who preferred to be called Mwalimu in Kiswahili or
teacher in English, has been a prominent leader on many
Pan-African issues.
</P>
<P>
He has successfully assembled the warring factions of Burundi
to start a tortuous peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
