<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Russia Not to Take Actions Against Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States
Wednesday called on Russia not to take any military actions
against Chechnya to wipe out terrorists that had planted bombs in
Russian cities, killing nearly 300 people.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said this was friendly
advice from the United States. Taking any military actions "could
actually worsen the situation," he added.
</P>
<P>
"They may be hitting terrorist targets as well, but what is I
think indisputable is that the attacks are causing increasing
numbers of refugees, and that is becoming a bigger problem," Foley
said.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials, including Prime Minister Vladimir Putin,
have said a full-scale land operation in Chechnya is one of
several military options under consideration to root out militants
hiding in the regions. Those militants invaded Dagestan from
Chechnya recently and set bombs in several cities, including
Moscow, after they were driven out of Dagestan by Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
Foley said Washington did not question Russia's right to take
military actions against these militants, but he said the military
response might be misdirected because Washington does not believe
the authorities in the Chechen capital of Grozny have any control
over the militants.
</P>
<P>
"As a practical matter, we don't believe that the rebels who
invaded Dagestan from Chechnya answer to central authority there.
We believe that they are independent actors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Foley said Russia's military operations could complicate
attempts to start a dialogue between Moscow and Chechen leaders on
the rebels' invasion of Dagestan and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We fear that a continued escalation will make a dialogue much
more difficult to take place and to succeed," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
