<HEADLINE> Russia Continues Pounding Rebel Positions in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian federal planes
launched bombs and missiles on rebel positions in the breakaway
republic of Chechnya for the seventh day running Wednesday amid
reports of a pending ground campaign in the North Caucasus
province.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry said Wednesday air force planes carry out
50-70 missions daily in Chechnya and that they only target
positions belonging to guerrillas, mainly oil refineries and oil
storage facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency, quoting a military source in the
headquarters of the federal troops in Daghestan, said the
positions taken by federal troops on the administrative border
with Chechnya indicate that a ground operation against guerrillas
there can begin any time soon.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin said he had
never ruled out a ground operation in Chechnya but Moscow would
"never allow a repetition of what happened in Chechnya in
1994-1996."
</P>
<P>
"There will be no storming or attacks which can led to
unnecessary casualties among the troops," Tass quoted Putin as
saying in Cheboksary.
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything possible to protect the lives of the
soldiers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The air campaign came after thousands of Chechen-led militants
streamed across the border into Daghestan and several apartment
building explosions in Moscow and other major cities that killed
over 300 people. Islamic Chechen militants were believed to be
behind the blasts.
</P>
<P>
"I have become completely convinced that the state policy of
stepped-up fight against terrorism is correct and should be fully
implemented," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister said Russia will not take it out on
the Chechen people for the horrible acts of terrorism committed on
its soil, referring the housing block blasts.
</P>
<P>
"Revenge is a bad feeling and the state has no right to be
guided by it," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
