<HEADLINE> Trimble Denies Secret Deal Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, Britain, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Northern
Ireland's main Protestant party leader David Trimble Wednesday
dismissed suggestions that his party was planning to soften its
line on weapons decommissioning to form a devolved government with
Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
At the annual Labor Party Conference in Bournemouth, the Ulster
Unionist Party leader rejected speculation that he was considering
a plan to set up an assembly executive with Sinn Fein on condition
that the Irish Republican Army begins decommissioning within four
weeks of its formation.
</P>
<P>
Trimble stuck to his position that a weapons handover must
happen before an assembly executive is formed. He said he had yet
to see any commitment from Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
IRA.
</P>
