<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Peace Process, Success: Mowlam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOURNEMOUTH, Britain, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Britain's
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam stressed Wednesday that the
peace process in the province is a success.
</P>
<P>
A a Labor conference fringe meeting in Bournemouth, Mowlam said
fundamental shifts had occurred despite the series of failed
deadlines leading to the current review led by former U.S. senator
George Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
As evidence, she pointed out a drop in the victims of sectarian
violence in Northern Ireland from 100 a year a decade ago to seven
so far this year.
</P>
<P>
While stressing "every death is unacceptable," she said this
was evidence of a profound change.
</P>
<P>
A fall in unemployment from 16 percent to 6 percent in the same
period equally resulted from the peace process, she added.
</P>
<P>
But she admitted the process was far from complete and faced
serious dangers.
</P>
<P>
"The difficulty we're facing is as simple as neither side
trusting the other. That is the bottom line," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe if either side took the risk, took the moral high
ground, then the process would move," she added.
</P>
<P>
The review of the peace process chaired by Mitchell will resume
Thursday. 
</P>
