<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Orphans Grow Rapidly in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The number of Zambian AIDS
orphans is expected to grow from an estimated 80,000 in 1991 to
600,000 by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The growth in poverty, increasing disease burdens and the
collapse of household coping capacities is taking a heavy human
toll in Zambia, a report by United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) / Zambia Program of Cooperation for Women and Children
said.
</P>
<P>
The report was released in the Mid Term Review meeting in
Lusaka on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the child mortality reduction trends of the 1970s
have been reversed, with the infant mortality rate growing from 80
to 113 for 1,000 live births between 1980 and 1992 and the
mortality rate for children under five rising from 150 to 202 per
1000. With rising HIV infection rates, these figures are expected
to increase by as much as 20 and 45 percent respectively by the
year 2000, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Zambia today is at the heart of the
African AIDS belt which stretches from Uganda and Kenya southwards
to eastern South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The overall goal of the UNICEF/Zambia program of cooperation
for 1997- 2001 is to strengthen Zambian capacities to promote
sustained improvements in the survival, development and welfare of
women and children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish PM Sees Grounds for Optimism on N.Ireland Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern said in Dublin, the Irish capital, on Wednesday that there
were grounds for optimism for the peace process in Northern
Ireland despite current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
He told the Irish parliament it was encouraging that Sinn Fein
leaders and pro-British Unionists were still talking to each other
and giving grounds for hope, a Reuters report said.
</P>
<P>
"I do believe, and still believe, that these gentlemen are
nearer than people think. It's not easy but I still think we're
not that many miles apart," the report quoted Ahern as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ahern said the deadlocked peace process, currently under review
by George Mitchell, a former United States senator, was intact.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that there was no alternative for the Good Friday
Agreement, which was signed in 1998 after ceasefires by the Irish
Republican Army opposed to British rule and Protestant guerrillas
loyal to Britain.
</P>
<P>
Both Ahern and his British counterpart Tony Blair attended the
signing of the agreement last year.
</P>
<P>
"We have not got a Plan B, we're not contemplating a Plan B, we
haven't discussed a Plan B...We have an obligation to implement
the Good Friday agreement, voted on by the people, and there
shouldn't be another plan," Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
The accord envisaged new political institutions that would take
account of the conflicting allegiances of the province's majority
Protestants and its pro-Irish Catholic minority.
</P>
<P>
But its implementation and the formation of a power-sharing
executive in Northern Ireland has stalled over the issue of
disarming guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, head of the Ulster Unionist Party, refuses to
sit with Sinn Fein, the IRA's political ally, until the IRA
disarms while Sinn Fein insists it is committed to democracy, has
fulfilled its obligation and brands the Unionist stance as a
breach of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ahern said he believed Mitchell's review of the Good Friday
accord would take longer than expected.
</P>
<P>
"Originally we did say the end of September. It will go on into
a good part of October, that's my judgment," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
