<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scotland Opens First All-Gaelic School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Scotland opened its first
all-Gaelic public primary school Wednesday, aiming to safeguard
one of Europe's oldest languages from extinction.
</P>
<P>
The 109 students at the Ashley Street Gaelic School in
Scotland's biggest city of Glasgow will have all their classes in
Gaelic until the third grade, when they will be offered English as
a separate course, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
Although Gaelic-only units exist within other primary schools
in Scotland, this school will offer everything in Gaelic -- even
playground signs and the cafeteria menu.
</P>
<P>
Once the language of most Scots, Gaelic has been in sharp
decline and is now spoken by only about 55,000-65,000 people --
mostly across central Scotland and in the Highlands and Western
islands. The language is closely related to Irish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
