<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Priority on AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- HIV/AIDS must be recognized as
the biggest catastrophe to hit the world and it will generate an
economic catastrophe which will cause political catastrophe if not
controlled, a United Nations official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Zambia / United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
Mid Term Review meeting, UNICEF Regional Director for Eastern and
Southern Africa Urban Jonsson criticized the western countries for
only spending 150 million U.S. dollars annually on AIDS in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO is "spending billions of dollars per week on
Kosovo, a cause which really doesn't solve much."
</P>
<P>
Jonsson said such improper global prioritizing by the West
should be stopped and resources fairly shared among the poorest
states.
</P>
<P>
He said the international community should be involved more and
more in the issue of AIDS because the epidemic would not be halted
"through conferences in Geneva, Nairobi or Lusaka".
</P>
<P>
Jonsson also urged African countries to declare the disease a
disaster and channel more finances toward it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
