<HEADLINE> Belgrade Slams Mortar Attack on Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia Wednesday
slammed the Tuesday "mortar attack on Serbian civilians" as "a
gruesome terrorist act" by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA),
saying that the incident mirrors the failure of KLA
transformation.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here, the Yugoslav Mission to the
United Nations said that the mortar attack on Serbian civilians at
the Kosovo Polje market on September 28, 1999 has created two
deaths and 39 injuries. The two killed were Serbian civilians, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The attack "is a gruesome terrorist act which exposes the
fatuity and charade of the 'demilitarization' and the so-called
transformation of the terrorist KLA into the Kosovo Protection
Corps."
</P>
<P>
The transformation, under an agreement between the U.N. mission
in Kosovo and the KLA, constituted "a flagrant violation of the
Security Council resolution 1244, in particular its provisions
relating to the demilitarization of KLA," said the news release.
</P>
<P>
"The (transformation) decision appears to have been designed to
preserve, even strengthen, the Kosovo Liberation Army as a tool of
the ethnic cleansing of the Serbs and other non-Albanians in
Kosovo," it said.
</P>
<P>
"The massacre is eloquent proof that, notwithstanding its
alleged demilitarization and transformation, the KLA continues to
possess large quantities of heavy weapons," and that the
international peacekeeping force in Kosovo (KFOR) and the U.N.
Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK) "continue to turn
a blind eye and, by extension, to encourage the Albanian
terrorists and separatists in their drive to create an ethnically
pure Kosovo," said the news release.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Yugoslavia demands that the Security Council "take
energetic measures to ensure full property and personal security
of all residents in Kosovo", "prevent the terror and vandalism of
Albanian terrorists, carry out their full disarmament and have
those responsible for crimes against civilians apprehended and
tried," it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
