<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcano Guagua Pichincha Affects Quito </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The volcano Guagua Pichincha in
northern Ecuador Wednesday sent off ashes which fell on Quito and
other populated areas, said the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The expulsion of the ashes culminated a chain of earthquakes
registered in the volcano over the previous 24 hours, according to
spokesmen from the Geophysical Institute of the National
Polytechnic School.
</P>
<P>
The volcano has a height of 4,784 meters and is 10 kilometers
to the east of Quito.
</P>
<P>
The ashes were emitted without any explosion, almost at the
turning of the clock Wednesday, and the earthquakes began again at
5 a.m., local time, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
One part of the dome in the western sector of the volcano
collapsed a short time ago due to heavy rains and the recent
explosions, according to technicians at the Geophysical Institute.
</P>
<P>
The ashes which fell on Quito covered the southern streets in
the capital, as well as houses and vehicles. In the nearby valley
of Los Chilos, the streets were covered with a light film of ash.
</P>
<P>
The government is maintaining the Orange Alert due to the
activity of the volcano, meaning the surrounding residents were
evacuated. The inhabitants of Quito are fearful of an eruption.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Ecuadoran President Jamil Mahuad urged people
in the capital city of Quito to remain calm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
