<HEADLINE> OAU Vows to Cement Partnership With U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General
Salim Ahamed Salim of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) said
here Wednesday that his organization is determined to strengthen
the cooperation and partnership with the United Nations in efforts
to put an end to conflicts and give peace a chance in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We, at the OAU, also attack great importance to the enhanced
cooperation between the Organization of African Unity and the
United Nations, convinced, as we are, the partnership which exists
between the two institutions is mutually reinforcing," he said.
</P>
<P>
Salim made the statement as he was speaking at the Security
Council, which convened an open session on Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The OAU takes particular pride in the partnership we have been
able to build with the United Nations and the regional economic
communities in Africa and we definitely look forward to the
strengthening and consolidation of this partnership for peace,
particularly as we prepare to enter the new century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the leadership of Kofi Annan, who became the first black
African to head the world body in 1997, the United Nations is
growingly concerned with how to end various conflicts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Salim extended a welcome to Annan's recent proposal for the
deployment of a 6,000-strong U.N. force for Sierra Leone, which is
aimed to promoting the peace process in the West African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
