<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Alerts EU Over Helms-Burton Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Spanish Foreign Minister Abel
Matutes Wednesday warned that any action involving the application
of the Helms-Burton law would have negative repercussions in the
relation of Spain and the European Union (EU), with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
According to Matutes, the Spanish government will use all its
available methods to stop U.S. sanctions against Spanish
businesses with investment in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
In a hearing before the Foreign Commission of the Congress,
Matutes said that any eventual application of sanctions in virtue
of the Helms-Burton law "would trigger reaction by the EU and its
governments".
</P>
<P>
Matutes said the governments of Europe would request economic
compensation and also begin a suit against the United States, in
view of the understandings agreed upon by the United States and
European countries in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister considered as "serious and worrysome" the
contents of the letter sent in July to the tourist group Sol-Melia
by U.S. State. in which it stated that it was "revising your
activities in Cuba".
</P>
<P>
He said he asked the U.S. government should refrain from
sanctioning this group.
</P>
<P>
Matutes revealed on Wednesday, that in his letter to U.S
Foreign Secretary Madelaine Albright, he warned that if the U.S.
government began actions against the Spanish company in Cuba, it
would attract "negative reactions" as much in the "excellent
bilateral relations" between Spain and the United States as in
those between the European Union and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
For its part, according to Matutes, the European Commission,
gave instructions to its delegation in Washington to warn the
United States "of the risks undertaken by the adoption of measures
of application of the Helms-Burton law against a European
company". 
</P>
</TEXT>
