<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet Charges "Are Not Torture": Lawyer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The lawyer for former Chilean
leader Augusto Pinochet on Wednesday concluded their case at an
extradition hearing in London by saying the charges against the
retired general do not amount to torture.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, is wanted by Spain to answer 35 charges of
torture, including beatings, sexual abuse and sleep deprivation,
said to have been carried out by the Chilean police between 1973
and 1990.
</P>
<P>
On the third day of the five-day hearing held at Bow Street
Magistrates' Court in central London, Clive Nicholls, the lawyer
for Pinochet, said his client "does not contend to condone any of
the conduct described in these charges."
</P>
<P>
Nicholls argued that much of the conduct described in the
charges did not amount to torture as defined in judgments of the
European Court of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
"They may amount to inhuman and degrading treatment, but that
is another matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
The hearing, which openned on Monday and scheduled to last to
the end of this week, is to decide whether the charges against
Pinochet are extraditable.
</P>
<P>
Nicholls argued that there was nothing to sustain the
allegation that Pinochet was engaged in a campaign of "widespread
and systematic torture" after 8 December 1988, the date the House
of Lords, the highest court in Britain, ruled earlier this year
that Pinochet could not be prosecuted for torture before this.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, who currently live in a hired mansion in Surry,
south-west of London, was arrested on Spain's request last October
in a London hospital where he was recovering from a minor
operation.
</P>
<P>
The retired general repeatedly said he would not accept any
ruling against him except that from a Chilean court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Set Up Special Fund to Lower Seismic Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, 29 September (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Ministry of
Public Works and Territorial Planning has drafted a bill to set up
a special fund meant to lower the seismic risk with buildings, the
official Rompres news agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The fund is planned to be fuelled by a one percent share on
taxes levied on buildings. It will be employed for consolidation,
expertise and connected works. According to the laws in force,
expert technical surveys of buildings may be made free of charge,
upon the request of people who own buildings.
</P>
<P>
For consolidation works, soft credits, at an interest rate of 5
percent may be granted. The ministry classified as first-grade
seismic risk 90 buildings in Bucharest after technical surveys,
mostly built in the inter-bellum period and having more than four
floors. They have been rocked by numerous tremors in time, the
heaviest of all being the one in 1977, of 7.4 grades on the
Richter open-ended scale. Bucharest was the worst hit by that
tremor, reporting around 90 percent of the over 1,000 victims.
</P>
<P>
The Public Works and Territorial Planning Minister Nicolae
Noica says damage like that in Turkey of last August however will
not occur in Romania in a similar situation, since this country
has for many years applied rigorous norms of seismic protection in
constructions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
