<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Organize Joint Investment Promotion Missions to Developed Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN has decided to
organize joint investment promotion missions to Japan, Europe and
the United States to attract foreign investments from these
sources.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Trade and Industry George Yeo briefed a
press conference about this decision as he outlined the outcome of
the 31st ASEAN Economic Ministers Meeting held here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yeo said the missions will be led separately by Malaysian
Minister of International Trade and Industry Rafidah Aziz, himself
and Thai Minister Abhisit Vejjajiva to Japan, Europe and the
United States and the events are slated to take place in February,
March and June next year.
</P>
<P>
Yeo also said the main objectives of the events are to show
that ASEAN is on the road to recovery and to provide ASEAN the
opportunity to market the countries collectively.
</P>
<P>
A concerted effort by all ASEAN members to organize these
events would be a striking demonstration of ASEAN's unity and
common purpose, Yeo underlined.
</P>
<P>
The idea of organizing a series of joint ASEAN investment
promotion missions to the major developed countries to draw
investment back to the region was raised by Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong during his visit to Brunei in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
Goh officially proposed the joint investment roadshows by ASEAN
in July during the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting and he said the
specific proposal is aimed at showing that ASEAN is back in
business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
