<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Prospect Remains Dim for Cyprus Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit discussed the Cyprus
issue on Tuesday, but the prospect for holding Cyprus peace
negotiations still remains dim.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of Clinton-Ecevit meeting had been viewed a basis
on which U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan would decide whether to
invite the two sides of Cyprus back to the negotiating table at a
later time.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops occupied the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the international community has been trying to
bring the two sides to the negotiation table for reunification
through a bicommunal settlement. But no tangible progress has been
achieved.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side had hoped Clinton would pressure Ecevit
to push forward with the talks.
</P>
<P>
But reports said no plan for Cyprus was proposed by Clinton in
his meeting with Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Clinton announced that he would send his special envoy
Alfred Moses to the region as early as next week to assess the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that Annan is likely to hold off his decision
until Moses completes his mission.
</P>
<P>
After the Clinton-Ecevit meeting, political parties in Nicosia
expressed their concern over the prospect of the peace-making
efforts in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We feel disappointed and displeased that nothing positive
came out of the meeting," said the ruling right-wing Democratic
Rally party leader Nicos Anastassiades.
</P>
<P>
"President Clinton avoided exerting any pressure on Turkey,"
said Speaker of House of Representatives (parliament) Spyros
Kyprianou, who is the leader of the center-right Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
It is widely reported that Ecevit told Clinton that Turkey must
be recognized as a European Union candidate if progress is to be
made on Cyprus, and that Ankara would take no action on Cyprus
until the outcome of the EU Helsinki summit in December.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior U.S. official, during his meeting with
Clinton, Ecevit reiterated the Turkish side's well-known position
that talks can only take place if the breakaway Turkish Cypriot
state in northern Cyprus is recognized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
