<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition's Demonstration Ends Without Troubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi opposition's siege
of the Election Commission (EC) Thursday ended without any
troubles as protesters staged demonstration far off the EC office
protected by huge riot police.
</P>
<P>
The government put up a strong security bulwark around three
kilometers of the EC at Sher-e-Bangla Nagar with police and para
military forces as well as barbed-wire fences.
</P>
<P>
Opposition activists who proceeded towards the EC office did
not make any attempt to break the barricades, rather sat down
where intercepted by police.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)-led opposition alliance
staged the demonstration demanding immediate resignation of Chief
Election Commissioner Muhammad Abu Hena in order to pave the way
for holding free and fair polls.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the start of siege program, BNP held a rally in the
city. Addressing the rally, BNP Secretary General Abdul Mannan
Bhuiyan said that the chief election commissioner would have to
stand down as he claimed 70 per cent people of the country have no
confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
Panic virtually griped the city life Wednesday as the
government expressed its determination to resist the
opposition-sponsored siege program by imposing ban on any
assemblage, demonstration, procession around the EC office.
Thousands of police and Bangladesh rifles were deployed Thursday
around the EC office to maintain peace and law and order there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
