<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Road Loan to Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Approved
Thursday a 25 million-U.S.-dollar loan to Mongolia for the
building of a strategic road which will eventually link
Ulaanbaatar, the country's capital, with the border of China.
</P>
<P>
The Second Roads Project Development to Mongolia will also
usher in reforms in Mongolia's road sector to boost transport
efficiency in the country, the ADB said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
The project will improve 200 kilometers of a road in the
country which will eventually be extended to Sainshand and Zameen
Uud completing a paved link between Ulaanbaatar and the border
with China.
</P>
<P>
An earlier ADB-financed project is currently rehabilitating 312
kilometers of the northern link from Ulaanbaatar to Altanbulag on
the border with Russia.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is estimated at 33.5 million U.S.
dollars equivalent and the balance of the cost will be borne by
the Mongolian government.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loan will come from its concessional Asian Development
Fund and will be repayable over 32 years, including a grace period
of 8 years.
</P>
<P>
The interest charges will be one percent per annum during the
grace period and 1.5 percent per annum thereafter, said the ADB.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
