<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rewi Alley's China House Turned into Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Rewi Alley would have smiled
to see his old Beijing house turned into a museum, which opens
today in the Chinese People's Association for Friendship with
Foreign Countries (CPAFFC) compound.
</P>
<P>
CPAFFC President Qi Huaiyuan addressed the ribbon-cutting
ceremony, and highly commended Alley's devotion to the
revolutionary cause of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Alley, a celebrated New Zealand writer and educator, Qi said,
spent the last 60 years of his life in China where he dedicated
himself to understanding and explaining New China, which was
largely unknown in most of the world.
</P>
<P>
The house was home to Rewi Alley for almost 30 years before his
death in 1987, and had also been the residence of other
international friends including American journalist Anna Louise
Strong, American civil rights movement leader Robert F. Williams,
Chilean painter and peace champion Jose Venturelli, and Japanese
social activist Saionji Kinkazu, according to Qi.
</P>
<P>
In commemoration of these international friends, the CPAFFC
decided to renovate the house and turn it into a museum, named "
Friendship Museum," Qi said.
</P>
<P>
Alison Mann, charge d'affaires of the New Zealand Embassy to
China, also spoke at the ceremony. "Throughout his sixty years in
China, Rewi Alley acted as a bridge of friendship between New
Zealand and China," she said.
</P>
<P>
Present at the ceremony were officials from government
departments and foreign diplomatic envoys in Beijing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
