<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministers Reaffirm Commitments to Accelerate Implementation of ASEAN Economic Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN economic ministers
have reaffirmed the commitments of their countries to accelerate
implementation of the ASEAN Investment Area (AIA) Agreement and
the ASEAN Free Trade Area Agreement (AFTA) in a bid to enhance
economic recovery and to deepen regional economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Trade and Industry George Yeo briefed a
press conference about this as he was outlining a statement on the
outcome of the 31st ASEAN Economic Ministers Meeting held here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Before the press conference ASEAN economic ministers signed the
Protocol on the Special Arrangement for Sensitive and Highly
Sensitive Products, under which agricultural products were
included in the Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT)
Agreement for AFTA in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the ministers welcomed the decision of the
AFTA Council to eliminate import duties on all products and to
target to achieve this objective by 2015 for the six original
members and by year 2018 for the new members of ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also welcomed that the six original members will
eliminate tariffs on 60 percent of their products by the year
2003, it added.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the ministers agreed on acceleration of AFTA
with the six original ASEAN member countries committed to reducing
tariffs to 0-5% for 85 percent of products in the Inclusion List
of the CEPT Scheme by 2000 and Laos and Myanmar making unilateral
moves to accelerate their schemes under AFTA.
</P>
<P>
Touching on investments, the statement said the ministers
welcomed the decision of the AIA Council to expand the scope of
the AIA Agreement to cover service components with each of the
sectors under the AIA Agreement, namely manufacturing,
agriculture, forestry, fishery and mining.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Yeo announced that ASEAN will organize
joint investment promotion mission to major developed countries to
draw investment back to the region.
</P>
<P>
As a concerted effort by all ASEAN members, he said, the events
scheduled to take place in first half of next year aim to show
that ASEAN is on the road to recovery and to provide ASEAN the
opportunity to market the countries collectively.
</P>
<P>
Yeo also said that the ministers held ASEAN countries are on
the road to recovery and the growth prospects for the ASEAN
countries have improved this year after the steep downturn in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also noted there remain some uncertainties that
could affect the economic recovery in Asia and ASEAN countries
must therefore continue to be vigilant and keep up efforts to
enhance business environments through pro-enterprise policies and
economic restructuring, Yeo said.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the ministers pledged to give the strongest
support to the launch of a new round of multilateral negotiations
within the WTO when WTO ministerial meeting is convened at Seattle
later this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, ASEAN economic ministers will meet
informally in their Retreat in Yangon, Myanmar in May 2000 and
formally at the 32nd ASEAN Economic Ministers Meeting in Bangkok,
Thailand in October 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
