<HEADLINE> P &AMP; G Has Full Confidence in China's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble, one of the
world's largest consumer-goods producers, will raise the ratio of
its global business in China from the present three percent to 10
percent in the next 10 years, P &AMP; G Chairman Durk Jager said here
today.
</P>
<P>
China is a country with great prospects and latent market
potential, providing a big space for development for P &AMP; G
products, said Jager, who is in Shanghai to attend the "99 Fortune
Global Forum.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Jager said it was not
expected that P &AMP; G would have grown at such a rapid pace in China.
P &AMP; G has opened 11 joint ventures in China with a total
investment of 300 million U. S. dollars since its first enterprise
opened in Guangzhou in 1988.
</P>
<P>
P &AMP; G is a leading foodstuffs, cosmetics and detergent producer
with annual sales of 35 billion U.S. dollars, and is ranked among
the top 500 multinational corporations by the Fortune Magazine.
</P>
<P>
P &AMP; G has experienced rapid development in China since 1992
when China accelerated its pace of economic reforms. The company
has set up a relatively complete market survey system throughout
China, created a research center together with Qinghua University
to develop products suiting the needs of Chinese consumers, and
has pursued a policy of buying equipment and raw materials where
the products are made.
</P>
<P>
At present, the amount of raw materials P &AMP; G had purchased in
China has exceeded 250 million U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jager attributed P &AMP; G's achievements in China to rapid
economic growth, an improved investment environment, and support
from Chinese customers.
</P>
<P>
The decision of reinvestment in China was made for two reasons:
a large population and great scope for further development, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe China will become more prosperous. We have full
confidence in the economic growth of China," he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
