<HEADLINE> Barak: No Compromise on Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak told officers of the Northern Command of the Israel Defense
Forces (IDF) Thursday that Israel will not compromise on its
security.
</P>
<P>
Israel will never compromise, or make any concessions over the
issues of its security and sovereignty, Barak told the officers
while inspecting the Command outposts.
</P>
<P>
Amid intensified fightings inside the security zone in south
Lebanon in recent days, Barak was on a trip to the north in a bid
to gather first-hand information about the worsening situation in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Israeli military group Hezbollah, or Party of God, and
the pro-Israeli South Lebanese Army (SLA) recently intensified
their mutual attacks against each other, while the IDF's fighter
jets launched constant air raids against the "terrorist targets"
inside or outside the security zone.
</P>
<P>
The fighting has inflicted property damage and casualties on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
A SLA soldier was killed and two others were wounded on
Wednesday at Rshaf, bringing to seven the number of SLA members
killed since the beginning of this month. Among them was Fwazi
Sagghir, chief of the SLA intelligence in the central sector of
the security zone, who was killed in a bomb blast on the perimeter
of the zone in the western sector on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the zone has caused worries among
Israelis. Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephrain Sneh inspected
the zone Wednesday, warning the military escalation may delay
Israel's planned withdrawal from south Lebanon next July.
</P>
<P>
There has been no sign of ceasefire in the security zone so far.
</P>
<P>
During the day, Hezbollah and SLA reportedly attacked each
other's positions inside the zone, while fighter jets from the IDF
launched more air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the self-proclaimed security zone in 1985 and
since then, military groups such as Hezbollah have been fighting
against the Israeli occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
