<HEADLINE> Japan to Provide Quake-hit Turkey Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister
Komura Masahiko said on Thursday that Japan would extend 23.6
billion yen (223 million dollars) in loans to Turkey to help its
after-quake rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
Japan made the decision in response to Turkey's request, Komura
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be used for purchasing necessary goods and for
covering the transportation cost of 1,500 makeshift shelters to be
sent from Japan, he said.
</P>
<P>
A powerful quake, measuring 7.4 on the Richter scale, shook
northwestern Turkey on August 17, killing more than 15,000 people.
</P>
