<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Postpones Cabinet Reshuffle Due to Nuke Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi said Thursday night he would postpone the cabinet reshuffle
scheduled for Friday due to an unprecedented nuclear accident in
Ibaraki Prefecture, northeast of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi made the remarks to a group of reporters after convening
a high-level emergency meeting on a radiation leak at a uranium
processing plant in Tokaimura, where radiation levels at and
around the plant remained high.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi had planned to reshuffle his cabinet Friday to expand
the current coalition between the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
(LDP) and the Liberal Party (LP) to include New Komeito, Japan's
second largest opposition party.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred shortly after 10:30 a.m., when three
workers were exposed to radiation after a fire broke out at a
nuclear fuel-related facility in Tokaimura.
</P>
<P>
The accident forced Tokaimura's board of education to instruct
all schools in the village to close their windows and keep their
students indoors.
</P>
<P>
The village also issued an evacuation advisory to 50 households,
or about 150 people, located within a 350-meter radius of the
facility. The village also advised residents living within a 10-
kilometer radius of the facility to stay indoors.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka told a press
conference Thursday night that abnormal reactions in the uranium
processing plant may be continuing.
</P>
<P>
"There is a strong possibility that abnormal reactions are
continuing inside even now," the top government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Nonaka said the Japanese government has set up a new disaster
headquarters under Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, replacing one
headed by Science and Technology Agency chief Akito Arima.
</P>
<P>
He also said that although evacuation orders have already been
issued by local governments, Tokyo will consider further
evacuations as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
Nonaka, who had said in a news conference earlier in the day
that further damage was not likely, said the situation was worse
than expected.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government's Nuclear Safety Commission said the
leakage may have been caused by a "criticality accident," in which
a nuclear fission chain reaction becomes self-sustaining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
