<HEADLINE> EU To Conclude Strategy for Global Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Trade ministers of the
European Union (EU) states are due to hammer out Friday the "
remaining glitches" in the EU's strategy for the ministerial
meeting of the World Trade Organization (WTO) in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting in Florence, Italy, on October 1, the
ministers will aim to settle on "a unified and coordinated policy"
for their so-called "Millennium Round" of wide-ranging trade
negotiations, although there is no guarantee that it will be
formally launched at the Seattle meeting as planned, the EU said
in a newly published report.
</P>
<P>
They will focus on trying to win over as many WTO members as
possible to the EU's vision, report said.
</P>
<P>
At the Florence meeting, the EU ministers will put forward a
draft document, urging the WTO to appeal to the needs of poor
countries so that market-opening initiatives could attract global
support in the fields of environment, agriculture and information
technology, the EU indicated.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also be Pascal Lamy's first major meeting
since he was confirmed as the European Trade Commissioner earlier
this month, the report added.
</P>
<P>
After the Florence meeting, the EU's strategy for global trade
talks will be passed by the foreign ministers of EU member states
at the General Affairs Council meeting in Luxembourg on October 11
for formal approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
