<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Countries Face Skilled Personnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries
face a shortage of skilled personnel needed for the growth and
modernization of the region's mining sector, according to a study
by the Southern African Development Community's Mining Sector
Co-ordinating Unit, the weekly Business reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study said that the region had mere eight engineers per one
 million people, compared with upward of 500 engineers per one
million people in Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
It revealed that the region's mining sector had 57,000
skilled personnel, with South Africa accounting for 83 percent of
this figure. Zambia, with 10 percent of the total, is in second
position.
</P>
<P>
The study recommended that the numerical insufficiency of
skilled personnel for the mining sector be resolved by expanding
the intake of students in existing training institutions and
through the introduction of a quota system to accommodate more
students from the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
This can be achieved through improved financial and materials
support from governments and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Government's mining departments should also be strengthened to
better cope with the private sector in their regulatory and
promotional roles and small-scale mining, said the study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uygur Man Bikes to Beijing to See National Day Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- After a four-month-long
bicycle trip, 70-year-old Sultan Mamut from the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region arrived in Beijing earlier this month to see
celebrations for National Day with his own eyes.
</P>
<P>
On May 20, Sultan started his journey on an old bike from a
small village in Jiashi County in the region's Kashi area, which
is about 5,000 kilometers from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time the old Uygur man had ever set out to
go so far from home. He took with him a bottle of water, a cloak
which he also used as a quilt at night, and five hundred yuan (
about 60 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
He can only understand a few sentences of Mandarin Chinese, and
when he was asked where he was going, he would answer "to Beijing,
" and when asked "What for.", he would say "to see Tian'anmen".
</P>
<P>
"I heard the celebrations for the 50th anniversary of the
founding of new China will be magnificent," said Sultan, who wears
a new suit and a colorful little Uygur cap, "and I want to show
the respect my neighbors and I have for President Jiang Zemin,
that's why I have come here."
</P>
<P>
He is now the second person from his village to have come to
Beijing. The first one came here 40 years ago to attend an awards
ceremony. Sultan's first impression of the capital city is that it
is "very large, very beautiful."
</P>
<P>
"During the journey, I received help from many people and most
of them were of Han nationality," Sultan said, "many Han policemen
provided me with mineral water, and Han farmers would take me into
their houses to spend a night."
</P>
<P>
Since he was not familiar with the roads along his journey, he
had to ask the way at almost at every crossroads. And sometimes he
had to wait for hours for someone he could ask.
</P>
<P>
"A middle school student walked with me for several kilometers
to show me the way, before he went to school," he recalled, "
because I could not figure out complicated sentences in the Han
language."
</P>
<P>
Sultan fell ill one month after he left home, and local people
bought him a ticket so he could return home. But he did not accept
the offer, and continued his journey after 15 days of rest.
</P>
<P>
When he arrived in Beijing with only 20 yuan left in his pocket,
it was a Han woman who led him to the office of the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region in Beijing, and lent him 100 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Ismail Amat, a state councilor who is attending a conference on
ethnic work in Beijing, came to see him, and officials from the
Ministry of Civil Affairs and the Office of the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region in Beijing took him to Tian'anmen Square where
he took many pictures to show his neighbors when back home.
</P>
<P>
"It is getting cold, you should not ride a bicycle back home,"
Ismail said to the old man, "we will arrange trip by train for you.
" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somalis March Against Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of people
marched through the main streets of the Somali capital Mogadishu
Thursday calling for an end to civil war and anarchy.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration was organized to support the proposals made
by the President of Djibouti, Ismail Omar Gelleh, at the recent
United Nations General Assembly in New York, searching for peace
and reconciliation for Somalia's lasting political crises.
</P>
<P>
The marchers waved slogans and placards carrying messages such
as "No More Lack of Government", "The Time for the Warlords is
over", and many others. The people also carried the photos of
President Gelleh and national flags of Djibouti and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The people have similarly shouted words advising the warlords
and their affiliated politicians that now they have the last
chance to follow the desires of the Somalis and quit their ill
intentions of the continuation of the civil war.
</P>
<P>
President Gelleh suggested an all inclusive peaceful
reconciliation conference be held in his country to find a
representative government for Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations, which also took place in many towns and
districts including Baidoa, Huddor, Beletuein, El-Bur, Merca, have
all called for the United Nations to implement the ideas by
Djibouti's president for finding a broad-based government for
Somalia in the very near future.
</P>
<P>
However, Professor Issa Mohamed Siad, the acting representative
of Hussein Mohamed Aidid, has characterized the proposal by
Gelleh as an intervention into Somali internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
In a smaller demonstration in South Mogadishu, the faction of
Hussein Aidid led by Mss Hawo Awaleh Abtidon blamed Djibouti,
which hosted two separate reconciliation conferences in 1991, for
Somalia's persisting crisis.
</P>
<P>
In those two meetings, Ali Mahdi Mohamed (an arch rival of late
 General Aidid) has been nominated as the interim president of
Somalia, but none of those governments had been functional.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the BBC Wednesday, Mahdi who has been in
Cairo for the past five months, has warmly welcomed the
initiative by President Gelleh of Djibouti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
