<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provincial Status Gives Chongqing More Development Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, which was once a
city of Sichuan Province in southwest China, has had greater
development opportunities since gaining provincial-type status in
March 1997.
</P>
<P>
Changing Chongqing from a city to a municipality, which was
approved by the 5th plenary session of the 8th National People's
Congress, was a result of China's further reform and opening-up
drive, said He Guoqiang, who was appointed Party secretary of
Chongqing in May.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, China's fourth, youngest, and largest municipality,
the other three being Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin, aims to
become an economic center at the upper reaches of the Yangtze
River. It will relocate millions of people for the Three Gorges
Dam project, according to He, who was governor of east China's
Fujian Province four months ago.
</P>
<P>
Since it became a municipality in 1997, Chongqing has enjoyed
more autonomy and more preferential policies extended from the
central authorities. It can now obtain more funds from the central
government and attract more investment from domestic and overseas
businesspeople, said He.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Chongqing's gross domestic product (GDP) grew at a
higher rate than the national average in the past two years. In
1997, industrial taxes and profits in Chongqing were up 20 percent
from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In the January-June period this year, Chongqing's industrial
sector reported a growth of 12.6 percent, three percentage points
higher than the national average level.
</P>
<P>
Despite these achievements, He said, Chongqing still has many
difficulties to overcome, including unprofitable state-owned
enterprises, poverty in some places, the relocation of people
around the Three Gorges Dam project area, and a deteriorating
ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has stepped up its poverty-elimination efforts. Thus
far, two million poor rural people have been added to those who
are secure in having adequate food and clothing. The first phase
of population relocation has been completed, and the second phase
is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing still lags behind in development compared with
Shanghai, Beijing and Tianjin. The per capita GDP of the these
cities is five times, three times and 2.9 times that of Chongqing,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, which has a population of 30 million and covers an
area of 80,000 sq. km, will take every opportunity to develop its
economy in a bid to catch up with more-developed eastern China
regions, He noted.
</P>
<P>
On prospects for Chongqing Municipality, He said it will make
greater contributions to China in the 21st century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
