<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Registers Trade Surplus In July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The first estimate for euro
zone trade with the rest of the world in July 1999 was a surplus
of 12.1 billion euros (12.7 billion U.S. dollars), compared with
13.6 billion euros (14.3 billion U.S. dollars) in July 1998, the
European Union (EU) statistical office, Eurostat, said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The revised June 1999 surplus was 8.0 billion euros (8.4
billion U.S. dollars), compared to 7.8 billion (8.2 billion U.S.
dollars) in June 1998. This gave a total surplus of 25.3 billion
euros (26.6 billion U.S. dollars) for the first half of 1999,
compared with 37.7 billion (39.6 billion U.S. dollars) in the same
period of 1998, the Eurostat said in a report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 15-country European Union also registered a
foreign trade surplus of 5.2 billion euros (5.46 billion U.S.
dollars) in July, compared with 7.8 billion (8.2 billion U.S.
dollars) in trade with the rest of the world in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat also said that there was a revised surplus of 2.4
billion euros (2.52 billion U.S. dollars) in June, against 3.0
billion (3.15 billion U.S. dollars) in June 1998. There was also a
deficit of 8.3 billion euros (8.7 billion U.S. dollars) in the
first six months compared to a surplus of 6.1 billion (6.4 billion
U.S. dollars in the same period last year, the Eurostat said.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration of trade balance in the whole EU region is
explained by the report as a four percent fall in exports over the
first six months of this year. Exports were weak across all main
product groupings, the Eurostat said.
</P>
<P>
Total imports remained the same as 1998, with the growth in "
machinery vehicles" counterbalancing the fall in "raw materials",
it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
