<HEADLINE> PRC Birthday Marked in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador to New
Zealand Chen Wenzhao gave a reception here Thursday, warmly
celebrating the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China (PRC).
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley appointed Simon Upton,
minister of State Services and associate minister of Foreign
Affairs and Trade as the representative of her and her government
to attend the reception.
</P>
<P>
Also attending was Parliament Speaker Doug Kidd.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the reception, Ambassador Chen briefed more than
270 guests about China's achievements in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
On the motherland reunification issue, Chen said the Chinese
people's great cause of the peaceful reunification of the
motherland is forging ahead continually.
</P>
<P>
"After Hong Kong's return in 1997, Macao will return to the
motherland on December 20, 1999. We will resolve the Taiwan issue
under the guidance of 'peaceful reunification, one country, two
systems' concept, realizing the complete reunification of the
motherland," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador noted 1999 is an important year in the
development of the Sino-New Zealand bilateral relations and it has
seen the exchange of visits by New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley and Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, he added, have agreed to establish a
21st-century-oriented relationship of long-term stability, healthy
development and all-round cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that there exists not only a solid base but
also a bright future for the development of an all-round friendly
relations and cooperation between the two countries," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
In his toast, Minister Upton said: "Over the past 50 years we
have witnessed tremendous change and growth in Chinese society and
advances in the prosperity of the Chinese people, for which we
congratulate you.
</P>
<P>
"This year has been a milestone in China-New Zealand
relations. The visit of President Jiang Zemin enhanced the mutual
understanding between the peoples of New Zealand and China."
</P>
<P>
"As we move into the 21st century," Upton said, "I am
confident that our countries will continue to enjoy the benefits
of a cooperative and dynamic relationship."
</P>
<P>
Present on the occasion were Georgina Te Heuheu, minister for
Courts; Guariki John Delamere, minister of Immigration; other
Parliament members; senior government officials; diplomatic envoys
of various countries in Wellington; representatives of friendly
organizations and overseas Chinese organizations.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday, Chinese Consul-General to Auckland Wu Zuqiu hosted
a reception in Auckland to mark PRC's 50th birthday. More than 350
people attended the reception. They included local senior
government officials, members of consular corps in Auckland, and
representatives of friendly organizations, overseas Chinese and
compatriots from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Toasting at the reception, Consul-General Wu said that the
Chinese people will have a sacred mission of reunifying the
motherland in the new century. He called on overseas Chinese in
New Zealand to contribute more to the cause.
</P>
<P>
Philip Warren, chairman of the Auckland Regional Council, said
in his toast that the founding of the PRC is one of the events of
the greatest significance in the 20th century. He spoke highly of
the achievements New China has made in the past 50 years and
affirmed the positive role China has been playing for the economic
stability in Asia and in the world at large by persisting in its
policy of reform and opening up to the outside world and in the
policy of not to devaluate its currency.
</P>
<P>
Warren noted that China should be allowed to get access to the
World Trade Organization as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The receptions were permeated with a warm atmosphere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
