<HEADLINE> Reported Secret Palestinian-Israeli Accord Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
Thursday denied a reported secret agreement between Palestinian
National Authority and Israel on the issue of settlements and
commencement of final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Culture and Information Yasser Abed Rabbo, also
leader of the Palestinian delegation to the final status talks,
told the "Voice of Palestine" radio that the settlement issue
constitutes the first priority of the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
This is particularly so because the current Israeli government
is pursuing the "robbery" policies of previous governments by
"stealing and occupying Palestinian lands under new forms", Rabbo
said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Israeli government was using Jewish
feasts to justify the delay in forming a final status negotiating
team, though the same feasts and celebrations did not put off the
heated settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Ministry of Housing and Construction had decided
last Sunday to build 1,000 housing units in the Adomim settlement
in east Jerusalem, an act duly denounced by the Palestinian
Authority as a violation of the Sharm el-Sheikh Memorandum and
detrimental to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The "Voice of Palestine" also announced that Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak was currently visiting settlements close to
Ramallah town in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Rabbo also denied reports attributed to official Israeli
sources that final status negotiations would be resumed in a few
days, emphasizing that no such day was fixed.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Authority has actually formed its final status
negotiating team a week ago, whereas the Israeli delegation has
not been formed until now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
