<HEADLINE> Palestinian Safe Passage to Be Opened on Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A safe passage between the
West Bank and Gaza Strip will be opened Sunday as scheduled in the
latest Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement, Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This subject has been discussed from every possible angle
over the years. Now the time has come to carry it out according to
the agreement that has been signed," Barak said during a visit to
the Northern Command of the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
The safe passage, which links the Gaza Strip with the West Bank
city of Hebron, will enable Palestinians to travel and transport
goods between the Palestinian self-rule areas for the first time.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sharm el-Sheikh agreement signed early this
month, the route would be opened Friday. It was rescheduled to
Sunday because Friday is the beginning of the Jewish weekend.
</P>
<P>
Only two days away from the deadline, however, difference
remains between Israel and the Palestinians over security
arrangements, according to radio reports.
</P>
<P>
Israel insists that it keep the right to make security checks
on passengers and vehicles and arrest suspected Palestinian
extremists on the route. The Palestinians said this would make
the route a "trap" rather than a free passage for them to travel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami said earlier
the opening of the corridor might be delayed due to the security
dispute.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm el-Sheikh agreement, a second safe passage
route linking Gaza and the northern West Bank town of Ramallah
will be opened early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
