<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Indonesian Military to Make Right Choice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen Thursday urged the Indonesian Military
(TNI) to make the right choice in the East Timor problem.
</P>
<P>
"The Indonesian military will be acting in a manner consistent
with Indonesia's national interests and international obligations
if they contribute to a peaceful solution in East Timor," Cohen
said at a press conference held here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He criticized TNI for its aiding and abetting violence in East
Timor in recent months, saying the Indonesian military is at a
critical turning point.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the military can play a key role by allowing a
process that is legitimate and credible or it can destroy hope for
a peaceful transition by refusing to respect human rights and the
rule of law.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the United States strongly supports
Indonesia's transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is an Indonesia that is democratic, prosperous,
united and stable," he said.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the military programs between two countries, Cohen
said he made it clear that the United States will not consider
restoring normal military to military contacts until the TNI
reforms its ways.
</P>
<P>
"The military must show restraint and respect for human rights
throughout Indonesia. It must be clear that the military operates
under civilian control," he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the People's Consultative Assembly, which will
convenes here Friday (October 1st), will take an important step in
its transformation toward democracy as it selects a new president.
</P>
<P>
During his one day visit, Cohen held discussions with President
B.J. Habibie, Defense Minister/TNI Commander Gen. Wiranto, ad
interim Foreign Minister/Coordinating Minister of Political and
Security Affairs Feisal Tanjung and Coordinating Minister for
Economy, Finance and Industry Ginanjar Kartasasmita.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also met General Chairman of the Indonesian Democratic
Party of Struggle Megawati Soekarnoputri, the only political party
leader he met during the visit.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, on the second leg of a five country tour of the region,
will leave here for Thailand on Thursday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
