<HEADLINE> Another Shiite Muslim Leader Killed in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Gunmen shot dead a Shiite
Muslim leader Thursday in Pakistan's Punjab province in the second
religiously motivated killing to target Shiite leaders this week,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
Ijar Rasoul Nagri, a lawyer and leader of the Shiite group
Tahreek-e-Jafria Pakistan (TJP), was killed in the city of
Gujranwala, some 60 kilometers north of Lahore, the provincial
capital, said the police.
</P>
<P>
Nagri was in his vehicle with his daughter when the gunmen
passed on a motorcycle killing him on the spot. The gunmen escaped
and it wasn't immediately known if Nagri's daughter was injured.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility for the incident, but TJP is
blaming rival Sunni Muslim groups for the second killing of its
leaders in a week.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, in Pakistan's southwestern Balochistan province,
another TJP leader, Khurshid Anwar, was shot dead in his car with
his daughter and a bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
The police are looking for three activists of Sipah-e-Sahaba, a
violent Sunni Muslim group which has been blamed for hundreds of
attacks on Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Most of Pakistan's 140 million people are Sunni Muslims.
Hundreds of people have been killed in recent years in the
conflicts between a small number of Muslim extremists from both
Islamic sects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
