<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Assures to Act Swiftly on Pay Hike Petitions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
assured the public Thursday that it will act swiftly on petitions
for salary adjustments to help the people cope with recent oil
price increases triggered by the global market.
</P>
<P>
But Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican also said that "the
process should not be politicized even as genuine interest of
labor needs to be addressed."
</P>
<P>
Barican said in a news release that the issue should not be
looked upon as an opportunity to push for wages levels "that will
merely result in further price increases, job losses and lack of
international competitiveness."
</P>
<P>
He said that what is being studied is the immediate effect of
the price increases on the cost of living and inflation.
</P>
<P>
"The government will not support petitions for wage hikes that
are not based upon the direct effect of fuel prices on inflation,"
Barican said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Philippine President Joseph Estrada said he sees the
need for salary increases but added that a decision on the matter
should also consider possible effects on inflation.
</P>
<P>
The president has directed regional wage boards to immediately
act on petitions for wage increases filed with them.
</P>
<P>
According to Barican, as of Thursday, there are nine petitions
for wage increases, ranging from 20 pesos (0.5 U.S. dollar) to 100
pesos (2.5 dollars) daily wage adjustments.
</P>
<P>
Barican said under the law, the wages boards are required to
conduct public hearings before they can issue an order granting
wage increase.
</P>
<P>
He said the Department of Labor and Employment will call for a
meeting early next week of all government representatives in the
various wage boards for consultations on the wage situation all
over the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
