<HEADLINE> Milan Enters a Protest against French Referee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 30 (Xinhua) -- AC Milan have officially
complained to UEFA about the performance of the French referee in
their Champions League 1-1 draw with Hertha Berlin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Milan vice-president Adriano Galliani had written to UEFA
General Secretary Gerd Aigner outlining his club's unhappiness
with Gilles Veissiere, according to local reports on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Veissiere booked five Milan players and ruled offside an injury
time strike from Leonardo, which Milan players and officials
insist was a legitimate goal.
</P>
<P>
Galliani made a scathing attack on Veissiere following the
match, saying he had cost Milan victory and adding "he has
something about Italians" - a reference to certain decisions he
made in last season's Juventus v Galatasaray and Inter Milan v
Manchester United matches.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to the UEFA, the vice-president wrote that "the
refereeing was not of to the standard for such an important match
and took the calmness out of the game."
</P>
<P>
Gattuso suggested referees may be looking out for diving from
Italian players. "Perhaps we Italians have gained a bad reputation
in Europe," said the former Glasgow Rangers midfielder. 
