<HEADLINE> Basic Education Should Precede Computer Revolution in Philippines: Senate President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Senate President
Blas Ople said Thursday that while universal computer literacy was
desirable, the government should first make elementary education
freely and fully available to Filipino children.
</P>
<P>
"It may be incongruous to be talking of Filipino children
invading the information highway when we consider that nearly four
million Filipinos are jobless," Ople said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the 31st management congress of the
Philippine Council of Management (Philcoman), Ople said efforts of
government and the private sector to keep abreast of the
technological revolution should continue.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that "we should not overlook the fact that
the Philippines remains a poor developing country, where 99
percent of the population lack a telephone, much less a personal
computer."
</P>
<P>
He added that the problem of education is dramatized by the
continuing crisis in school buildings or classrooms, the acute
shortages of competent teachers and textbooks.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 26 percent of the country's population are
functionally illiterate and therefore may not be trainable for
higher skills while a total of 13,000 villages lack a single
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
Ople called on the Philcoman to take an active part in the
country's poverty eradication program which he said, was "the real
challenge to management integration in the new millennium."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Consumer Confidence Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese consumers showed
growing confidence in the country's economic outlook as the Index
of Consumer Expectation (ICE) in August rose by 1.3 points over
July to 94.5 points.
</P>
<P>
The China Business Climate Monitoring Center under the National
Bureau of Statistics said in its August report that two other
consumer-confidence indices, the Index of Current Consumer
Economic Conditions (ICC) and the Index of Consumer Sentiment (ICS)
, both hit their highest points since January.
</P>
<P>
Among 4,200 people surveyed, 50 percent expect better national
economic performance in the next 12 months, up six percentage
points from July, while 20 percent are uncertain, the fewest since
January this year.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that 49 percent of those surveyed are
optimistic about the economy's strength for the next five years,
an increase of six percentage points over July.
</P>
<P>
And the proportion of people who remain pessimistic was reduced
to 11 percent, down two points from July.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said that consumers have gained more confidence
thanks mainly to the favorable economic situation in August and
the policies announced by the government to stimulate the consumer
market.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that people's expectations for their own
financial situation remain guarded, with 39 percent expecting a
better life, only up one percent from July.
</P>
<P>
Some 31 percent of those surveyed said that their financial
situation is better than before, a rise of four percent from July,
while 22 percent said it was "worse," down five points.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 61 percent of the people think this is a
good time to buy durable consumer goods, seven percent more than
in July, which may stimulate the household appliances market.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that strengthening consumer confidence will be a
positive factor for speeding up economic growth in the latter half
of this year, though it will still take some time to fully
activate the consumer market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
