<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Painting Delights American Social Activist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese-American social
activist Anna Chan Chennault today expressed her delight with a
portrait of her presented to her by the Luzhou Painting Studio in
Southwest China's Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
The two-meter painting, titled "Herald of Spring", is a
meticulous-style Chinese work done in soft colors. In the picture,
Mrs. Chennault is wearing a white cheong-sam, with her hands
crossed in front of her, posed against a blue background.
</P>
<P>
The artist, Wei Wensheng, said he spent three months on the
portrait, which was done on dacron cloth. He said that he had
never seen Mrs. Chennault in person, but relied on a photo and her
autobiography to re-create her likeness.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Chennault's husband, Gen. Claire Lee Chennault, was
commander of the US 14th Air Fleet during World War II. He
organized a group of American pilots, known as the "Flying Tigers,
" who transported arms and other materials, and joined in an air
raid supporting China against Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
Many of the pilots were killed during the war. The search and
recovery of their remains has been carried out in China's Mao'er
Mountain, where remains of ten pilots have been found.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, to celebrate the 10th anniversary of the establishment
of the Luzhou Painting Studio, Mrs. Chennault was asked to write
an inscription by local government official Ye Shangming, a former
follower of Gen. Chennault.
</P>
<P>
The portrait was painted and sent to Mrs. Chennault to express
their appreciation on the eve of China's 50th anniversary
celebration.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Chennault is chairwoman of the Council for International
Cooperation of the U.S. She has established several scholarships
and been named an honorary professor at many Chinese universities.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Chennault is scheduled to participate in tomorrow's
National Day festivities on behalf of the overseas Chinese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President Meets Japanese Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President Hu
Jintao said here today that it hasn't been easy for the Sino-
Japanese friendship to develop to its present level, an outcome
that should be treasured and carefully cultivated by both
countries.
</P>
<P>
Hu was speaking during a meeting with visiting President of the
Japan-China Friendship Center and former Japanese Vice-Prime
Minister Masaharu Gotoda.
</P>
<P>
Hu said he appreciates Gotoda's effort to increase bilateral
friendship, and stressed that both countries should keep history
in mind, develop the friendship into the future, and implement a
series of important consensus and cooperation agreements between
leaders of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
All this should be done in line with the principles set forth
in the "Sino-Japanese Joint Statement", "Sino-Japanese Treaty of
Peace and Friendship" and "Sino-Japanese Joint Declaration", he
added.
</P>
<P>
Hu called upon both sides to "push together the Sino-Japanese
good-neighborly friendly cooperative partnership devoted to peace
and development to the upcoming 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Gotoda said he is delighted to be visiting China at the time of
its 50th founding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
At the doorstep of the coming century, both countries should
further enhance friendly exchange and cooperation in all fields,
he said, adding in particular that the younger generations of both
countries should understand the history, enhance mutual
understanding and mutual trust, all of which are vital to opening
up the future of bilateral ties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
