<HEADLINE> Nigerian Police Begin 24-Hour Patrol in Big Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
directed the Nigerian Police Force (NFP) to embark on a 24-hour
patrol in capital Abuja and commercial center Lagos to curb the
rising crime in the two cities.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Chief Dapo Sarumi announced the decision
in Abuja on Wednesday after the weekly meeting of the Federal
Executive Council presided over by President Olusegun Obasanjo,
the New Nigerian newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the meeting expressed concern at the
rising wave of violent crimes in the west African country,
especially in Abuja and Lagos.
</P>
<P>
The decision to introduce the police patrol is aimed at
checking the rising crime rate in the two cities, he said, adding
that it would be extended to cover all parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Sarumi disclosed that the government had set aside 2.5 billion
naira (about 25 million U.S. dollars) to enable the police force
to carry out the assignment.
</P>
<P>
The money is used to purchase vehicles, communication
equipment, security gadgets and some auxiliary support, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the increasing destructive tendencies of the O'odua People's
Congress (OPC), the minister noted that "no terrorist organization
would be permitted to disturb the peace and safety of Nigerians in
any corner in Nigeria". 
</P>
