<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Sees Clove Sales Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- As the prices in the
world clove market have sharply increased from 1,000 to 3,000 U.S.
dollars per ton, Zanzibar expects a sales boom of this spice.
</P>
<P>
This year's consumer projection of clove in the world is 52,000
tons, a figure that is difficult to meet due to declined
production worldwide, sources from Zanzibar said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Potential buyers from Singapore have already come to negotiate
business deals with officials of the Zanzibar State Trading
Corporation (ZSTC), the sole clove buyer from local producers and
official exporter.
</P>
<P>
"The Singapore buyers want to haul all this season's crop
projected at 10,000 tons," sources said. "However, ZSTC is yet to
decide whether to sell all cloves to Singapore at this stage in
anticipation to higher exports prices in due course."
</P>
<P>
The dramatic increase of the clove prices has been caused by
low production of the crop this season, especially in the main
clove producers, Indonesia and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The cloves remain the prime cash crop accounting for more than
44 percent of the islands' Gross Domestic Product (GDP) and more
than 85 percent of the foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
During the last two months, the government has twice raised the
producer prices up to 600 Tanzanian shillings per kilogram (one
U.S. dollar equals 800 Tanzanian shillings at present) in an
attempt to motivate growers to pick all the crop.  
</P>
</TEXT>
