<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accused German Businessman Remains in Jail in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Accused German businessman
Helmut Hofer has been ordered on remand pending investigations
into remaining charges against him.
</P>
<P>
The Public Relations Office of Tehran's Justice Department
issued a statement Thursday, saying Hofer, who was cleared of
illicit sexual affairs, will remain in jail temporarily.
</P>
<P>
Hofer finally escaped a possible death penalty Wednesday after
standing a third trial at a Tehran public court, which dropped the
adultery charge against him.
</P>
<P>
Hofer's lawyer said the misdemeanor charges of improper
relationship still remain against him.
</P>
<P>
The official statement said Hofer was accused of having
"contact with suspicious elements." Iranian authorities usually
use the phrase to refer to spying. But the statement did not say
for whom Hofer had allegedly spied.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the court will issue its ruling after
completion of its investigations on all charges against the
57-year-old German businessman. A final verdict is expected within
a week.
</P>
<P>
Hofer had been sentenced to death twice previously by two
different courts for having an affair with a 26-year-old Iranian
medical student.
</P>
<P>
Under Iranian law, sex outside marriage is punishable by
flogging; but if the man is not Muslim, he faces capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was initially sentenced to death in January 1998. Iran's
Justice Ministry ordered a retrial after Hofer insisted he had
converted to Islam before having sex with the woman.
</P>
<P>
He was again convicted and sentenced to death. But in February,
the Supreme court rejected the verdict and ordered a third trial.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was freed on bail in April, but arrested again in August
on charges of "links with foreign elements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
