<HEADLINE> World Bank Chief to Visit Nigeria Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- World bank chief James
Wolfensohn will pay a four-day visit to Nigeria next week and he
will meet with President Olusegun Obasanjo and other senior
government officials, News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the first by Wolfensohn to the country, he
will also hold discussions with private sector operators, donor
agencies, non- governmental organizations and the press on the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The country's oil fueled economy has run into dire straits
after years of mismanagement of its income, particularly during
the 15 years of military rule that ended on May 29 when the civil
elected President Obasanjo came to power.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based World Bank and its sister institution, the
 International Monetary Fund (IMF), are in the forefront of an
international campaign to prod the new Nigerian civilian
administration to undertake the structural reforms to qualify for
a reprieve on its estimated 30 billion U. S. dollars foreign
debt.
</P>
<P>
President obasanjo and key officials argue debt relief would
enable the country sustain the gains of its democracy.
</P>
<P>
"It would be difficult to extend the dividends of democracy to
the citizens with the present debt profile," the president said in
his maiden address to the United Nations general assembly in New
York last week.
</P>
<P>
During his visit the World Bank chief would also deliver a
keynote address at a conference being organized for national
legislators by the Nigerian government in collaboration with the
Bank and the development policy center, the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
