<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria to Squeeze Concession from Israel: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Syria has hardened its
position on restarting the stalled Israeli-Syrian talks in an
attempt to squeeze concession from Israel in negotiations over
the fate of the Golan Heights, a local daily said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Hebrew-language Haaretz said Damascus is demanding that
Israel not only withdraw its troops on the Golan Heights back to
the border before the Six Day War erupting on June 5, 1967, during
which the strategic plateau was seized, but also pull back from
some areas west of the line.
</P>
<P>
These areas in question, at the eastern shore of the Sea
of Galilee, were defined as "demilitarized zones" in the
Israeli-Syrian armistice agreement signed in 1949 following the
war which broke out after Israel proclaimed a state in May
1948.
</P>
<P>
Damascus does not mean to gain control over these areas, but
rather challenge Israel's sovereignty over them, the paper said.
From the Syria point of view, Israel is barred not only from
stationing troops in those demilitarized zones, but also from
carrying out development work there.
</P>
<P>
Israel has established several collective farms in the zones,
insisting that the armistice agreement did not ban civilian
development.
</P>
<P>
Ze'ev Schiff, a senior military analyst of Haaretz, said the
new Syrian position aimed at making it easier to bring about an
Israeli pullback to the border of June 4, 1967 by giving the
impression that Damascus had backtracked from its demand on the
status of the demilitarized zones.
</P>
<P>
Syria insists that no peace with Israel would be achieved
without an Israeli troop withdrawal from the Golan Heights back
to the June 4, 1967 border.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held on-and-off talks since the Madrid Middle
East Peace Conference in 1991 before they broke out in early
1996.
</P>
<P>
Since Prime Minister Ehud Barak took office two months ago
pledging to revive the Middle East peace process stalled in the
last three years, Syria and Israel have exchanged a considerable
number of indirect messages expressing interest in resuming the
talks.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides have yet to find a common formula to proceed
with. Syria demands that the negotiations be restarted from where
they were left off, saying former Israeli government of Yitzhak
Rabin had promised a full withdrawal from the Golan.
</P>
<P>
Israel denied the existence of such a promise, and Barak has
said Israel would not return to the June 4, 1967 border.
</P>
<P>
In the last few weeks, both Israel and Syria have intensified
their diplomatic efforts to seek international support for their
positions.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the annual United Nations General Assembly
session Wednesday, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy urged
Syrian President Hafez Assad to stop hesitation and begin talks.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Israel would not accept the Syrian demand
which he said would turn the final outcome of negotiations as a
condition for starting the talks.
</P>
<P>
In an unexpected move, President Bill Clinton held talks with
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa at the White House
Wednesday. But the presidential mediation failed to produce a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Washington is optimistic that the stalled Israeli-Syrian talks can
be kick-started despite the remaining obstacles.
</P>
<P>
Having held separate talks with Levy and Sharaa on the
sidelines of the U.N. session in New York, Albright said neither
side had budged but both had showed seriousness in reopening the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Danny Yatom, Barak's chief of staff, said Wednesday that he
believes the Israeli-Syrian talks could be resumed "in the coming
weeks" despite difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Navy Denies Rumor on Mutiny During Kosovo War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- French navy has denied a widely
spread rumor that 60 marines staged a mutiny on board the aircraft
carrier "Foch" during service in the Kosovo War this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of the navy weekly "Blue Collars" said that 15
marines did not finish their service on board "Foch" during war
because of health problems, and six others were sent home because
of improper behavior.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified retired navy officer told the media that 60
young marines serving on short term contracts were sent home,
because they could not stand the condition of life, the pace of
work and the discipline aboard the ship.
</P>
<P>
"Foch" was the flagship of the French fleet stationed on the
Adriatic Sea from January 26 till June 3.
</P>
<P>
It suspiciously called at the Italian port Trieste twice,
during which the mutinous marines could have been subdued by
military police from France and flown home on military aircraft,
according to the rumor. 
</P>
