<HEADLINE> Former Tanzanian President in London for Leukemia Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Former Tanzanian President
Julius Nyerere, who is in a London hospital for leukemia, is under
stable condition, a Tanzanian official here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"His condition is stable now," a spokeswoman for the Tanzanian
High Commission in London said. But she refused to give details.
</P>
<P>
"We can only tell you that no operation is planned on him
because of his age. He is too old," she said.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, 77, was admitted to St Thomas's Hospital in London
Friday, in what the East African country's president Benjamin
Mkapa described as a "very critical condition."
</P>
<P>
The former president has been a major figure in post-colonial
Africa and earned international respect for his integrity and
intellect. He has for the past four years led regional efforts to
bring peace to Burundi, which borders Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
He led the then Tanganyika to independence from Britain in 1961.
After retiring as president in 1985, he kept on playing an
advisory role in both Tanzanian politics and African affairs.
</P>
<P>
Doctors diagnosed Nyerere as suffering from a chronic form of
leukemia in August, 1998. 
</P>
