<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet Extradition Ruling to Be Made on October 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The magistrate hearing the
case of whether former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet should be
extradited to Spain to face human rights charges said Thursday he
would announce his judgment late next week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of a four-day extradition hearing held in
Bow Street in central London, Magistrate Ronald Bartle said the
ruling would be made at 1000 GMT on Friday, October 8.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, in the closing hour of arguments before the court,
Clive Nicholls, Pinochet's lawyer, said the court must consider
whether the charges against Pinochet actually amounted to torture.
</P>
<P>
He said Bartle had to consider whether what had happened was
actually torture as was alleged in the charges filed by Spain.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, was arrested last October in a London hospital
while recovering from a minor operation. A Spainish judge asked
for him to be extradited.
</P>
<P>
The retired general, who ruled Chile from 1973 to 1990, did not
attend this week's hearing which began on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But he is expected to be present when the judgment is announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
