<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Meets U.S. Defense Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie here on Thursday met the visiting United States Defense
Secretary, William Cohen, and discussed with him the East Timor
issue.
</P>
<P>
During the 90-minute meeting, Cohen asked about the East
Timorese refugees who fled to Indonesia's East Nusa Denggara
Province after the autonomy ballot in the territory on August 30
and urged the Indonesian government to create peace for East
Timor, sources at the presidential palace disclosed.
</P>
<P>
But the sources did not say what president Habibie told Cohen
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 230,000 East Timorese have arrived
in the East Nusa Denggara province and their arrival has created
many problems in the area.
</P>
<P>
Later, Cohen met Indonesian Defense Minister and Commander of
Armed Forces Gen. Wiranto. They discussed the East Timor issue and
the neutrality of the Indonesian military in the issue as well as
the development of democracy in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto told Cohen that at present Indonesian military is
conducting internal reforms and taking a neutral position in
politics by not supporting any political party in the country.
</P>
<P>
On security in East Timor, Wiranto said the issue has fully
been in the hands of multinational peace-keeping forces which
entered East Timor on September 15. Indonesian military could only
help the peace-keeping force as a "joint consultative group,"
spokesman of the Indonesian military Maj. Gen. Sudrajat quoted
Wiranto as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived here on Wednesday night from Australia, will
also meet with the leader of the Indonesian Democratic party of
Struggle (PDI-P), Megawati Soekarnoputri, before leaving for
Thailand on Thursday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
