<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's National Games Showcase Minority Nationalities' Talents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- China's Sixth National Games
for Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities which concluded
here on Thursday, showcased the sporting talents of the country's
minority nationalities on a multi-cultural arena.
</P>
<P>
And mutual understandings and communications among the 56
nationalities of the world's most populous country has also been
greatly boosted.
</P>
<P>
The seven-day sporting and cultural gala, participated by
athletes from the 55 minority nationalities, successfully
concluded at a grand ceremony Thursday afternoon in the Great Hall
of the People, located by the giant Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurated in 1953, the quadrennial event has enjoyed a steady
progress, growing from a modest field of 300 to one of China's
major sporting gatherings with 8,500 athletes and performers
featuring over 100 competitive and demonstrative events this year.
</P>
<P>
Colorful is the word to depict the Games, where sports such as
Dragon boat races and the game of "Qiang Huapao" both originated
in southern part of China are not only competitive but also
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
And the contest of Mogolian-style wrestling, or "Borg" as it is
called in Inner Mogolia Autonomous Region, was participated by 170
athletes of different nationalities from 27 teams and it came out
an eye-catching show you can not expect from any of the mainstream
sports.
</P>
<P>
"For quite a long time, we significantly ignored the mass
participation and popularity of the traditional sports by minority
nationalities," said Sun Shouping, a professor from the Beijing
Sports Teachers' University.
</P>
<P>
"The success of the Minority Nationalities Games urged people
and minorities experts to further promote the traditional sports
across the country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Competitions of this year's Games were held in the cities of
Beijing and Lhasa, capital city of southwestern China's Tibet
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The timing of the Games coincides with the celebrations for the
50th birth of the People's Republic of China founded on October 1,
1949, and the 40th anniversary of the democratic reforms
undertaken in Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The next version of the quadrennial national event will be
hosted by Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Soar, Dollar Falls in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose sharply in
Tokyo Thursday, with the key Nikkei index closing above 17,500 for
the first time in six trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 323.18 points, or 1.87
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 17,605.46.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, surged 48.72 points, or 3.34 percent, to 1,
506.83..
</P>
<P>
After opening at the day's low of 17,307.22, the Nikkei index
stayed in plus territory throughout the day, supported by the yen'
s stabilization at a relatively weak level, traders said.
</P>
<P>
A news report on a business tie-up between Sakura Bank and
Deutsche Bank stirred stock purchases later in the afternoon. The
report, which said the two banks have agreed to tie up to provide
services in the securities business field, boosted not only Sakura
Bank but also other financial issues.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the main section increased to 559.75 million shares
from 373.50 million shares Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers overwhelmed
losers 1,084 to 195, with 68 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar fell to the 105
yen level after the Bank of Japan (BOJ) disappointed players by
saying its injection of additional liquidity in the morning should
not be seen as monetary easing.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 105.64-67 yen at 5 p.m., down
from 107.02-05 yen at 9 a.m., and from 106.95-107.05 yen in New
York overnight. The dollar was traded at 106.89-92 yen in Tokyo
late Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
