<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expressway on West Bank of Taiwan Straits Taking Shape (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- An expressway on the west bank
of the Taiwan Straits, which links Fuzhou, capital of east China's
Fujian province with Xiamen, one of the country's special economic
zones, will open to traffic on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Li Xinghua, an official with the Ministry of Communications,
made the announcement today in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Li said the expressway is part of the artery from Fuding in
northern Fujian to Zhaoan in southern Fujian. Construction of the
680-km artery started in 1994 and is expected to be completed in
2002, with a total investment of 24.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Chen Dongsheng, vice director of the Regional Economy Society
of China, said that the artery will significantly relieve the
traffic bottleneck that has long interfered with Fujian's economic
growth and, more importantly it will be extended to connect China'
s three key economic regions -- the Yangtze River Delta, the Pearl
River Delta and the Gold Triangle in south Fujian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
