<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 08:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Continues to Fight Against PKK: Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's military has said
that it will continue military operations against the outlawed
Kurdish Worker's Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The office of the chief of staff of the Turkish Armed Forces
announced Wednesday that the struggle against the PKK terrorism
will continue until the last remaining terrorist is made unable to
pose threat, Turkey's Hurriyet (Freedom) newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The office said that the PKK is still carrying out
anti-government activities though its imprisoned leader Abdullah
Ocalan called on his men to lay down their arms and leave the
Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish
state in southeastern Turkey. The conflicts have claimed over
37,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Ocalan urged a group of 20-25 militants to surrender
to the Turkish security forces to show the sincerity for peace.
But the office pointed out that the declaration of surrender is
nothing more than propaganda.
</P>
<P>
The local NTV reported Wednesday night that Turkey had
launched a cross-border military operation against the PKK rebels
sheltered in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
With the support of fighter planes and armored helicopters,
the 5,000-strong Turkish security forces entered 10 kilometers
deep into northern Iraq and killed at least 16 PKK militants
there, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has set up many camps to shelter thousands of its
militants based in northern Iraq since the Gulf War in 1991. It
often launches raids on Turkey's military and civilian targets
from the Iraqi territory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
