<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blind Man Wins Discrimination Case against Sydney Organisers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A blind man won a
discrimination case on Thursday when he forced Sydney's Olympics
organisers to produce a braille version of their ticket book,
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission found the
Sydney Organising Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG) had
discriminated against Bruce Maguire by refusing to provide him
with a 47-page ticket book in braille, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner William Carter said 41-year-old Maguire had been
at a disadvantage because he was unable to access the information
in the book which was needed to apply for a ticket to the 2000
Games.
</P>
<P>
He ordered SOCOG to provide him with a braille version and
consult with Maguire to ensure he had every opportunity to
participate in getting a ticket.
</P>
<P>
Outside the commission, Maguire, said he was overjoyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
