<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Marks World Maritime Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong maritime circles,
an associate member of the International Maritime Organization (
IMO), gathered Thursday to mark the World Maritime Day together
with 155 worldwide IMO member states.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this year's occasion is "IMO and the New
Millennium". The IMO was created in 1948 and the annual World
Maritime Day was first held on March 17, 1978 to mark the date of
entry into force in 1958 of the IMO Convention.
</P>
<P>
In a message marking the occasion, IMO Secretary-General
William O'Neil urged the shipping sector to continue to foster a
culture of safety with quality as its fulcrum as they were
preparing for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
O'Neil noted that during the past 40 years, IMO achieved a
great deal of success in dealing with its prime objectives.
</P>
<P>
Accidents and total losses of ships have gone down steadily, he
said, adding that the amount of oil getting into the sea from
ships has been cut by as mush as 60 percent and the number of
major oil spills reduced by half.
</P>
<P>
In the new millennium, the world's population continues to grow
and so the need for food and goods will increase, he added,
anticipating that shipping would play an even more important role
because ships remained the best, most economical and most
environmentally friendly means of transport available.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that crew training must be improved and the
standards of everyone involved in shipping, on shore as well as at
sea, will have to be raised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Traditional Sports Marketing Chance for Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Traditional sports in China
are playing a twofold role -- promoting people's health and local
economies as well.
</P>
<P>
It is especially true to areas with large community of minority
nationalities in the country, where traditional sports events are
often taken as marketing opportunities to promote local economy.
</P>
<P>
"Seize the chances," said an expert attending China 's Sixth
National Games for Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities,
which close here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Hans, China's 55 minority nationalities have about
nine percent of the country's total population of 1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
The quadrennial National Games and their local versions have
played an important role in promoting the economies of the hosting
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
In the southwestern province of Yunnan, for example, the six
provincial minority nationalities games held so far and the Fifth
National Games for Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities
staged in Kunming four years ago have greatly encouraged the local
enthusiasm in the construction of sports and infrastructure
facilities.
</P>
<P>
in 1995, Yunnan launched large-scale construction projects for
staging the fifth National Minorities Games in Kunming. Highways
were built to link Kunming and various tourist spots and seven
airports were constructed or re-built. When a the airport rebuilt,
Kunming became the fifth Chinese city with international air
service.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan's network of 10 airports now provides a much easier
transportation, which has thus greatly contributed to the success
of the on-going '99 World Gardening Fair Kunming.
</P>
<P>
Bao'an, a minority nationality in Gansu Province in the
northwest, is famed for the manufacture of various types of well-
decorated daggers, with the skills handed down through generations,
and popular game of "Dagger Chasing".
</P>
<P>
The game-turned sport has stimulated dagger production, which
has increased local people's incomes as well as tourist industry.
A village with large a Bao'an community in the province has almost
all the families involved in dagger manufacturing, with one family
earning over 30,000 yuan RMB (3,500 U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
"Dagger manufacturing has now been one of our means to improve
our life," said 38-year-old Ma Junfu, member of the Bao'an
Minority and one of Gansu's dagger chasers participating in the
Beijing Games.
</P>
<P>
The authorities of Longjing city in the Yanbian Korean
Autonomous Prefecture in northeastern Jilin Province had succeeded
in winning the right to host the inaugural provincial minority
nationalities games in 1991. They took the event as a marketing
chance for their rich sources of fruits and a fruit festival right
after the games attracted a surprisingly big attendance from other
parts of China. Their products are now well-known in China.
</P>
<P>
"The sporting events come out a good marketing chance for us
now," said Li Xuexiu, an official of the Jilin provincial
delegation at the National Games in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
In Zhenyuan County of Qiandongnan Mao and Dong Autonomous
Prefecture in southwestern Chinese province of Guizhou, the annual
dragon boat races always attract teams and tourists from both
Guizhou and other provinces. With hotels overbooked and sales up,
local residents enjoy an incomes rise at the occasion. Local
organizers are planning to hold larger races in the future.
</P>
<P>
Lhasa, the other venue of this year's National Games for
Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities, hosted competitions
including three medal sports, August 18-23.
</P>
<P>
Among the newly-built facilities for the Games there is a new
horse racing course complete with a 1,000-meter speed race track,
a 200m demonstration track and a 200-seat stand. It is China's
largest and best-equipped race course.
</P>
<P>
The competitions attracted 2,500 athletes and officials and
over 12,000 tourists to the capital city of the Region which
averages 4,000 meters above sea level. The sudden increase of
visitors brought about a full-house booking in almost all hotels
in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila Steps up Efforts to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government on
Thursday wrapped up its annual National Tourism Week (NTW), which
is just one of the measures it adopted to boost the country's
tourism.
From September 26 to 30, various tourism-related activities
highlighted the celebration of this year's NTW with the theme
being "Preserving World Heritage for the New Millennium."
</P>
<P>
Tourism Secretary Gemma Cruz Araneta said that the latest NTW
aims to remind the public of the importance of the tourism
industry to the overall development efforts of the country.
</P>
<P>
It also aims at highlighting the role the industry plays in
helping preserve Filipino culture and the environment, Araneta
said.
</P>
<P>
This year's NTW celebration includes educational tours,
different types of exhibitions, presentations and forums on
tourism, games, quiz bee competition and other tourism-related
events at the regional level.
</P>
<P>
The celebration was in accordance with a government order
signed on October 1, 1996 declaring the last week of September of
every year as the NTW.
</P>
<P>
It also coincides with the World Tourism Day on the 27th day of
September of every year declared by the World Tourism Organization
(WTO).
</P>
<P>
Besides the NTW, the government is also drafting a "millennium
holiday" program geared to stimulate domestic tourism in the
second half of the year by taking advantage of the global festive
mood or "millennium mania" ahead of January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the millennium celebration began from
September 23, the start of the 100-day countdown, to December 31,
1999. The whole year of 2000 will be tagged as the New Millennium
Year.
</P>
<P>
The government is launching several worthwhile projects and
activities in line with the Philippine millennium celebration, and
one of the projects is to entice Filipinos residing and working
abroad to visit the country and join in the festivities.
</P>
<P>
This project involves mobilizing the government's overseas
offices to invite the more than six million Filipinos abroad to
visit the country for the millennium celebration and for tour
operators to design special tour packages for visitors.
</P>
<P>
Another measure the government adopted is to promote the
so-called ecotourism. It is provided for under an executive order
issued on June 17, 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the Philippine government, ecotourism is "low
impact, environmentally sound and community-participatory tourism
activity that promotes environmental understanding and education,
and yields socio-economic benefits to the concerned community."
</P>
<P>
The government has created a National Ecotourism Council (NEC),
which is now in the process of identifying ecotourism potential
sites in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Local governments are also looking for spots suitable for
ecotourism and required to submit plans for its developments to
the NEC.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the government has also prepared a list of tourism
projects for the youth aimed at raising their historical,
cultural, ecological and other tourism-oriented concerns by giving
them affordable tours.
</P>
<P>
Under these projects, young travelers can avail themselves of
discounted overnight or two-night trips to some of the country's
tourism resorts.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, tourism spending generated more than 2.4 billion U.S.
dollars and employed some 2.2 million workers in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Foreign visitor arrivals to the country for the first semester
of 1999 totaled 1,078,547, a 3.05 percent increase over last
year's 1,046,611 arrivals for the same period.
</P>
<P>
The government is confident that it will attract 2.25 million
foreign visitors for the year of 1999. In 2000, the government
expects that the visitor arrivals will reach 2.43 million.
</P>
<P>
In a plan submitted to the Congress, the Department of Tourism
(DOT) said the country's tourism industry could be developed into
a "great and reliable employment source" and could absorb up to
3.71 million workers by 2007.
</P>
<P>
As for external factors, the DOT stated that the improving
economic conditions of the country's major source markets from
Asia will contribute to the sustained positive growth of arrivals
for the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The DOT also believes several global factors, including growing
middle-class and well-educated travel groups, expansion and
modernization of transportation and infrastructure systems will
also promote the country's tourism industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
