<HEADLINE> SADC Urged to Create Smart Partnerships for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) states should work towards creating a
system of smart partnerships to foster economic growth and
development, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe made the call ahead of the Third Southern African
International Dialog conference to be held in Victoria Falls next
week, the Herald newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's second largest
city, Mugabe stressed the need for a culture of unity and dialog
between government, private sector and the labor.
</P>
<P>
"What we intend to achieve is to build into our system the
oneness and togetherness between government, private sector, labor
and citizens which will make us look at things together," said the
Zimbabwean president.
</P>
<P>
"At the meeting, we also want to see how the concept of smart
partnerships has been applied to practice," he said.
</P>
<P>
In tackling the region's economic development needs, the smart
partnerships idea could be used to pool resources, work out a
common regional agenda and foster a "win-win" scenario, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We can establish industries in areas that are depressed or
that have lacked development for quite a long time," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
There are resources that cannot be utilized, like gas in
Zimbabwe, he said, asking "Why don't we pool resources together to
get the natural gas so that it can be utilized?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
