<HEADLINE> Sales Rise in Kenya's Export Processing Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Export volume among the
Export Processing Zones (EPZ) in Kenya rose to 1.64 billion
shillings (around 21 million U.S. dollars at current rate) in the
first half of this year, the Daily Nation newspaper said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chief executive Samuel Bundotich of the EPZ Authority said
Wednesday that it was a 45 percent increase from 1.13 billion
shillings (about 15 million dollars) recorded in the
corresponding period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the rise in export volume to new entrants to the
 processing zones and the business expansion of the existing
companies.
</P>
<P>
Bundotich cited the new entrants engaging in production and
export of sisal dart-boards, garments, tea, medicines among
others.
</P>
<P>
The companies have penetrated the regional market and are making
inroads into Britain and Brazil, he said.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive said his authority will continue
encouraging foreign and local businesses to enter into
export-oriented industrial ventures and penetrate fully the
global export market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
