<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Sets Zero Tariff AFTA Timetable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The ASEAN Free Trade Area
(AFTA) Council has agreed on a timetable for realization of zero
tariff under the AFTA Agreement, obliging its six original members
to eliminate import duties of all products by 2015 and the new
members by 2018.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the 13th meeting of the AFTA
Council held here Tuesday in preparation for the two-day 31st
ASEAN Economic Ministers meeting due to open on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As an interim measure, the council requires the ASEAN countries
to reduce 60 percent of their products to the 0% tariff by the
year 2003.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the ASEAN countries to implement the acceleration
package adopted by the ASEAN Summit held in Hanoi last year. The
measures announced by ASEAN leaders at Hanoi mandated that 85
percent of all products should meet the 0-5% tariff rates by the
year 2000 for the six original member countries of ASEAN, namely,
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The six members are also required to further reduce tariff
rates to meet the 0-5% target tariff rate for 90 percent of all
products by the year 2001 and for all products by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The acceleration package requires the new member countries of
ASEAN to maximize their tariff lines at 0-5% rates by 2003 for
Vietnam and by 2005 for Laos and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The AFTA Council affirmed that Cambodia, which was officially
admitted to the grouping at the end of April this year, has joined
the other ASEAN countries in trade liberalization under AFTA and
has submitted a package that will begin tariff reduction on
January 1, 2000, with its deadline to achieve AFTA being 2010.
</P>
<P>
Kong Vibol, Cambodian Secretary of State of Economy and
Finance, told the press conference after the council meeting that
the time frame is long enough for his country to meet the AFTA
target.
</P>
<P>
The council also requires ASEAN member countries to be ready by
January 1, 2000, for enactment of the next package of tariff
reduction under AFTA, under which, a total of 53,294 tariff lines,
representing 82.79 percent of all tariff lines, will be included
for tariff reduction in the year 2000 and the average tariff rates
for products under AFTA would be reduced from 4.86 percent in 1999
to 2.75 percent in 2003.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
