<HEADLINE> Clean Energy Being Used at Scenic Chinese Resort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Hotels in the Huangshan
Mountain area in China's Anhui Province have substituted gas with
electricity as a major energy resource.
</P>
<P>
This helps reduce pollution in the country's major scenic spot
and workers no longer need to move heavy fuel tanks or coal loads
to the mountain, according to Hong Wenhuan, a member of the
Huangshan's tourist administrative committee.
</P>
<P>
Coal took the place of pinewood in the late 1970s and then was
replaced by fuel and gas in the early 1990s. The administrative
committee has spent 35 million yuan (4.2 million U.S. dollars)
over the last few years on electric transmission facilities. A few
eco-friendly projects like incinerators, wastewater treatment
plants, and organic vegetables plots were started in the area.
</P>
<P>
This has brought the forest coverage up from 56 percent in 1979
to 83.41 percent in 1989 and environmental improvement projects
have brought economic returns to the mountain, which had 4.2
million tourists in 1998, and 1.1 billion yuan in tourist revenues,
more than 3,000 times the amount two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The mountain also was declared to be a model of combining hotel
management and tourist development by the United Nations' World
Heritage Committee in March, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
