<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman Excludes Foreigners from Real Estate Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- As from October 1, Oman
will only allow nationals to go into real estate business, forcing
expatriates who once dominated the business to exit, the
Dubai-based Gulf News daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Omani Ministry of Labor, Social Affairs and Vocational
Training has reminded all those concerned that October 1 is the
deadline for all expatriates to exit the real estate brokerage
profession, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The deadline was fixed six months ago in accordance with a
ministerial decision.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement released to the press, the ministry urged
business owners to abide by the decision, making clear that there
was no room for any extension in the deadline.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also urged young Omanis to use this opportunity to
train themselves in the real estate business, thus helping the
governmental policies for Omanization.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, labor inspectors will start
raiding real estate offices from October 2 to ensure complete
implementation of the decision.
</P>
<P>
Several low-paid jobs have already been set aside for Omanis
this year and more are to follow to ensure that no Omani remains
jobless. The private sector has been geared to meet the national
challenge.
</P>
<P>
Omani government has accelerated the pace of Omanization in
recent years, making it clear that a job which can be handled by
an Omani should not be left to a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of illegal foreign workers were sent home early this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
