<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore PM Warns against Over-Optimism on ASEAN Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong Thursday cautioned ASEAN countries against
over-optimism about the economic recovery and urged them to move
faster than APEC toward achieving free and open trade.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the point in his speech delivered at
the opening ceremony of the 31st ASEAN Economic Ministers Meeting
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Despite improvements in ASEAN economic indicators, Goh said, "I
would caution against any hasty conclusion that things would only
get better."
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN has to remain vigilant as both natural and man-made
catastrophes can hit us unexpectedly," he added.
</P>
<P>
Talking on the internal and external challenges facing ASEAN,
Goh briefly mentioned the major problems within the region, such
as the weak foreign investment in most ASEAN countries,
difficulties in several ASEAN countries caused by large corporate
debt overhang and non-performing loans, complex problems that
continue to dampen lending activities and will take long time to
resolve, and banks' wary attitude about extending new loans to
business.
</P>
<P>
Domestic resistance to reforms and restructuring as well as
social and political problems could also place additional
obstacles in the path towards recovery, Goh said.
</P>
<P>
As to how ASEAN should respond to these challenges, Goh
stressed that "As individual countries we will need to follow
through measures to reform and liberalize our economies... ASEAN
must be quick to seize new growth opportunities as the region
recovers."
</P>
<P>
Noting that opportunities in other parts of the world could
divert interest from ASEAN if the grouping does not measure up to
those regions in terms of providing an attractive, competitive
pro-business environment, Goh said "We could risk being sidelined
in the next wave of economic growth, or worse, hollowed out as
foreign trade and investments flow to those economies."
</P>
<P>
AS a regional grouping, ASEAN should act decisively by
implementing concrete collective measures to lift ourselves up,
the prime minister emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He urged the ASEAN economic ministers to make concrete plans on
his proposal for Joint Investment Roadshow, to accelerate
implementation of the ASEAN Free Trade Agreement and ASEAN
Investment Area agreements, to maintain the grouping's relevance
and interests in the global multilateral trading system, to
explore the usefulness of forming cross-region free trade
agreements with strategic partners and pursue commercial benefits
through accelerated trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said ASEAN should move faster than APEC
which has decided to achieve free and open trade by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN should consider an earlier deadline to achieve the Bogor
goals for trade liberalization, he added.
</P>
<P>
After the opening ceremony, the 31st ASEAN Economic Ministers
meeting entered into closed sessions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Earthquake Hits Turkish Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The 7.4-magnitude earthquake
on August 17 has seriously hit Turkish tourism and caused a loss
of 173 million U.S. dollars in this sector.
</P>
<P>
Local Daily News reported here Thursday that the Turkish
Association of Travel Agencies (TURSAB) determined that there are
not many collapsed hotels or travel agencies within the
quake-stricken region, particularly in Istanbul, but that
"convention tourism" has been significantly affected.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the TURSAB stated that a number of
conventions and meetings that were scheduled to be held in
Istanbul have been canceled.
</P>
<P>
Beyond the effects of the earthquake, the report also noted
that the tourism sector has been experiencing a difficult time
since the beginning of the year and that a number of people who
made reservations to vacation in Turkey have canceled them.
</P>
<P>
Following the quake, the number of people planning to visit
Turkey's holiday resorts dropped by 20-25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The quake not only affected foreign tourism, but also domestic
tourism, with many Turkish people wavering on their vacation plans
due to the initial quake and the aftershocks that have continued
to make themselves felt.
</P>
<P>
There is a loss of 65 million dollars from the canceling of
conventions, a loss of 105 million dollars from people cutting
short their vacations and a loss of 3 million dollars from the
Anatolia tours that cannot now be organized.
</P>
<P>
TURSAB Chairman Talha Camas demanded that the companies in the
tourism sector be supported financially, a serious promotional
marketing policy be implemented and efforts be carried out for the
tour operators abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
