month-long clampdown on the militant Palestinian organization.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim Brotherhood has sent a second letter to the
Jordanian monarch, asking him to intervene and end the crisis
after 21 Hamas members were arrested following the closure of
Hamas office in Amman on August 30, the English weekly Star
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hamas politburo chief Khaled Mishaal and spokesman Ibrahim
Ghousheh are in good health and treated with respect in a
Jordanian prison after they were arrested with four of their aids
last Wednesday after ending a visit to Iran, the Star said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, 15 Hamas members had been detained and they were
charged with engaging in illegal activities, possession of arms
and weapons and holding military exercises in Jordan as part of
its campaigns against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, or the Islamic Resistance Movement, opposes the peace
talks between Israel and the Palestinians and calls for a holy
war to liberate all Palestinians occupied by Israel to establish
an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan`s clampdown on the movement was apparently a preemptive
measure aimed at containing Hamas activities in the kingdom,
particularly at a time when Israel and Palestinians are making
progress in their peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been a firm supporter and broker in the Middle East
peace process after it signed a peace treaty with the Jewish state
in 1994. 
</P>
