<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Moves Into Aging Society </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua)-- People over age 60 will
account for 10 percent of China's population by end of this year,
signaling the coming of the aging society, according to a
projection of the State Statistical Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
The projection, based on census data at the end of 1998, shows
that people above age 65 will make up seven percent of the
population by the year 2000, another internationally-recognized
standard for an aging society.
</P>
<P>
The SSB said China now is home to 126 million people above 60,
taking up 20 percent of the world total, which would make China
the biggest aging society for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
Experts here attributed the aging of the Chinese population to
the drastic drop in China's birth and mortality rates, which have
resulted from improved living standards and medical conditions, as
well as the country's family planning efforts over the years.
</P>
<P>
The aging population would have a far-reaching effect on China'
s population and its social and economic development, the experts
said.
</P>
<P>
Government officials here said the government will take more
efforts to raise the general public's awareness of the aging
population and the challenges arising from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
