<HEADLINE> Soaring Price Boosts Confidence Of Zimbabwean Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean gold producers have
gained confidence from a sudden surge in gold spot price to a
remarkable 305.56 U. S. dollars per ounce this week.
</P>
<P>
The gold price soared up after 15 central banks of the leading
industrial nations agreed to limit the sales to a maximum of about
400 tons annually and also not to increase their gold lending
above current levels for the next five years, the weekly Business
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move has generated interest in the local gold mining
counters, which firmed and pushed the Zimbabwe Stock Exchange's
mining index through the 1, 000 barrier.
</P>
<P>
Gold producers, Ashanti Gold Zimbabwe, Falcon Gold and Rio
Tinto Zimbabwe registered gains on the back of the firm gold
prices on international markets.
</P>
<P>
Gold price rose to 305.56 dollars an ounce on the Hong Kong
Market in Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Chamber of Mines of Zimbabwe David
Murangari described the development as "good news" coming at a
time when there was gloom in the mining sector.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts welcomed the development as paving the way for a
new era in the gold business.
</P>
<P>
"A heavy weight has been removed from gold. The clarity on
central bank sales and regulation of the lease market are both
very positive," said one analyst with an asset management company.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is the third largest gold producer in Africa after
South Africa and Ghana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
