<HEADLINE> Three Workers Injured in Fire at Nuclear Plant in Central Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Three Japanese workers were
exposed to radiation Thursday in a fire that broke out at a
nuclear fuel-related facility in Tokaimura, Ibaraki Prefecture,
central Japan, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The radiation level outside the plant was 4,000 times above
normal, Kyodo quoted officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three workers, including one who is in serious condition,
were taken to hospital in Chiba Prefecture by helicopter after the
incident which occurred shortly after 10:30 a.m. (local time).
</P>
<P>
Uranium fuel is processed at the facility run by the Tokyo-
based JCO Co., previously called Japan Nuclear Fuel Conversion Co.
</P>
<P>
In the fire, blue flame was emitted, and the police said there
is strong possibility that it was a critical accident.
</P>
<P>
Police issued an evacuation advisory to three households near
the facility, while closing off an area in a 3-kilometer radius
from the plant.
</P>
<P>
An explosion and fire on March 11, 1997 at the Tokaimura
nuclear complex wounded 37 workers and some of the radiation
spread to Tokyo and neighboring prefectures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
