<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: History Of Tian'anmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On October 1, 1949, Chairman Mao Zedong stood on the Tian'anmen
Rostrum and proclaimed the establishment of the Central People's
Government of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The gate has a history of more than 500 years and is one of the
main structures around the Tian'anmen Square area. It was built in
1417 and was originally called Chengtianmen and was the entrance
to the imperial palace in the Ming and Qing dynasties.
</P>
<P>
It was destroyed twice by fire and was re-named Tian'anmen in
1651 during the reins of emperor Sunzhi of the Qing Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
It consists of massive blocks of stone coated in red and topped
by an imposing wooden structure with double eaves and a yellow
tile roof.
</P>
<P>
It has five archways and a moat, the Golden Water River,
running past it, and it is spanned by five marble bridges, one for
each archway. Each of the bridges is guarded by two stone lions
and two stone pillars carved with a cloud and dragon motif.
</P>
<P>
On both sides of the Gate there are two large-character slogans:
"Long live the People's Republic of China" and "Long live the
solidarity of the people of the world." Between them is a large
portrait of Chairman Mao.
</P>
<P>
There have been three different portraits of Mao Zedong on the
wall. The first, of Mao in a military uniform and wearing an
octagonal cap, appeared at the founding anniversary of the PRC. In
1950, it was changed to one of Mao in middle age, and in the 1970s
that was changed to the one that hangs there now, of Mao in the
1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
In 1961, Tian'anmen was listed as one of the nation's key
cultural relics by the State Council. In 1988, it was opened to
the public, and the admissions into the gate have topped more than
18 million since then.
</P>
<P>
This June, the Beijing government started a renovation and
repair project for the structure and it now has a lovelier and
more solemn appearance and is ready for the celebrations marking
the 50th founding anniversary of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0251 </DOCNO>
