<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cultural Relics Exhibited at Birthplace of Confucius </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A large exhibition of cultural
relics related to Confucius is being held in Qufu, Shandong
Province, his birthplace, to commemorate the 2,550th anniversary
of the birth of China's most important philosopher and educator.
</P>
<P>
According to Kong Xianglin, curator of the Confucius Museum,
part of the 280 relics on display were collected after the
founding of the People's Republic of China and some of them have
never been on display before.
</P>
<P>
He said that the most valuable pieces are works from the Ming
Dynasty (13681644), a portrait of Confucius, files from his home,
and relics excavated in Lu, a state during the Spring and Autumn
Period (770476 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
In ancient China, Confucianism was treated as orthodoxy and
deference was paid by emperors, officials, and the literati. His
home now has more than 80,000 relics, making it the largest
private collection in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
