<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> After 50 Years, China Finally Enjoys Olympic Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- It took not only 50 years
before China became a giant in the Olympic family, but a long and
rough road.
</P>
<P>
No one has witnessed more about the efforts China has made
toward the glory in the Olympics than He Zhenliang, who has been a
member of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) since 1981.
</P>
<P>
"It took several generations for China to achieve today's
status in the international sporting arena, " He said. "When we're
celebrating the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China (PRC), we should never forget their efforts."
</P>
<P>
After its establishment in 1949, PRC took part in five summer
Olympic Games, finishing fourth in the medal standings in 1984,
1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
But dating back to the 1952 Games in Helsinki, Finland, He said,
nobody could imagine China would win a medal. It was after the
opening of the Games that China received IOC invitation to
participate in the Games. The Chinese delegation, which had been
prepared to compete in soccer, basketball and swimming, left for
Helsinki via former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
When the Chinese team arrived in Helsinki, the Games had only
five days left and only one swimmer caught his competition.
However, "He was eliminated in the heats," He said.
</P>
<P>
After that, China stayed away from the Olympics as then the IOC
adopted the "Two-China" policy. In 1979, with China playing a
more and more important role in the world's political and economic
arena, the IOC realized that the Olympic Games will by no means be
called a real world sports meet without China.
</P>
<P>
In October 1979, at a meeting held in Nagoya, Japan, the IOC
Executive Board passed a resolution on the problem of China's
representation, confirming PRC as the representative of the
Olympic Movement in the whole of China, while Taiwan is allowed to
remain in the IOC under the name of "Chinese Taipei".
</P>
<P>
An end was put to the 21-year-long abnormal "two Chinas"
situation making it possible for athletes on both sides of the
Taiwan Strait to take part in the Olympic Games and other
international competitions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also means that the IOC recognized PRC as the
sole legitimate government of the country, and Taiwan is an
inalienate part of China.
</P>
<P>
Three months later, China sent 28 athletes for participation in
the Winter Olympic Games in Lake Placid, the United States.
Although they failed to win a single medal, the five-star Chinese
colors was finally raised in the Games after an interval of 28
years.
</P>
<P>
In September 1981, He Zhenliang, who had always had close
relationship with Chinese Olympic Movement, was elected an IOC
member.
</P>
<P>
"The Lake Placid Olympic Games showed that China had returned
to the Olympic family," He said.
</P>
<P>
But the real breakthrough was made in the 1984 Los Angles
Games, when sharpshooter Xu Haifeng broke the zero to win the
first-ever Olympic gold medal in China's history.
</P>
<P>
China collected a total of 15 gold medals, eight silvers and
nine bronzes in Los Angles, finishing only after the United States,
Romania and West Germany in the gold tally.
</P>
<P>
"The performance of the Chinese athletes were really
astonishing," He said. "The whole world was fully convinced that
China, which had a history of 5,000 years, was an indispensable
member of the Olympic family."
</P>
<P>
After the restoration of membership in IOC, China has
participated in six winter Olympic Games and four summer Games,
winning a total of 52 gold medals.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, after successfully hosting the 11th Asian Games,
Beijing, capital of China, launched a bid for the 2000 Olympic
Games. Although it lost to Sydney by two votes, "the bidding
campaign was one of the most important chapters in the development
of the Olympic Games," said He, then the first vice-president of
IOC.
</P>
<P>
Now, six years after it lost its first bidding efforts, Beijing
has stepped onto the track of bidding for the 2008 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"China has demonstrated its power in the Olympic Games over the
past two decades, " He said. "The bid showed that China will make
further contribution to the Olympic Movement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
