<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Accept 300 Refugees From E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand is ready to
accept about 300 refugees from East Timor after an urgent request
for assistance from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion, a Wellington-based newspaper, Thursday quoted
Prime Minister Jenny Shipley as saying the first 100 East Timorese
could arrive within a week.
</P>
<P>
But the East Timorese will be given only temporary refuge.
Shipley said New Zealand has been asked to accommodate the
refugees for three months, but will offer longer-term assistance
if asked.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government is still considering exactly how
many East Timorese the country can assist, but is likely to
confirm to the United Nations that it will take 300, she said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the New Zealand government has already
committed 500,000 NZ dollars (260,000 U.S. dollars) for
humanitarian aid in East Timor. 
