<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Gets US$66 Billion in Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners have invested
126
billion NZ dollars (66 billion U.S. dollars) in New Zealand, more
than three times the amount New Zealanders have invested overseas.
</P>
<P>
The level of foreign investment is bigger than the total value
of
New Zealand's economic production in a year, which is about 100
billion NZ dollars (52 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In a media release, Statistics New Zealand noted Thursday that
the
high level of foreign investment in part reflects big state asset
sales in the past decade, including Telecom, PostBank and Bank of
New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, New Zealanders have 40.3 billion NZ dollars (21
billion
U.S. dollars) invested overseas.
</P>
<P>
The 85.7 billion NZ dollar gap between the total value of
foreign
investments in New Zealand and that of New Zealand investments
overseas means that overseas residents earn more from their
investments in New Zealand than New Zealanders from their
investments
overseas, Statistics NZ said.
</P>
<P>
"This explains the level of the investment income deficit in
the
current account which has stood at around 6 billion NZ dollars
(3.12
billion U.S. dollars) or more per year since 1995 and is a
significant component of the overall current account deficit," it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
