<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> P &AMP; G Says It's Confident In China's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble, one of the
world's largest consumer goods producers, will increase its
business in China from 3 percent to 10 percent of its global
business over the next 10 years, its Chairman Durk Jager said here
today.
</P>
<P>
China has wide prospects and market potential and a lot of room
for development for P &AMP; G products, Jager said at the "99 Fortune
Global Forum in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that P &AMP; G had not expected such a rapid growth
in China. It has started 11 joint ventures in China since the
first one opened in Guangzhou in 1988, with total investment of
more than 300 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
P &AMP; G is a leading food, cosmetics, and detergent producer with
annual sales of 35 billion U.S. dollars. It has been ranked among
the top 500 multinationals by Fortune Magazine.
</P>
<P>
The company has seen rapid growth in China since 1992 when
China accelerated the pace of its economic reforms. It has set up
a relatively-complete market survey system throughout the country,
built a research center with Qinghua University to develop
products suited to Chinese consumers, and has a policy of buying
equipment and raw materials near where the products are made. The
raw materials it has purchased in China were worth 250 million U.S.
dollars, Jager says.
</P>
<P>
He attributes P &AMP; G's success in China to the rapid economic
growth, improved investment environment, and support from Chinese
customers. The decision to increase investment in China was made
for two reasons, namely, the large population and the scope of
further development. He said he believes that China will become
more even prosperous and has confidence in its economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
