<HEADLINE> Feature: Economy Equally Important as Traditional Sports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Traditional sports in China
are playing a double-folded role, promoting people's health and as
wel as local economies.
</P>
<P>
It is especially true to areas with large community of minority
nationalities in the country, according to experts attending China
's Sixth National Games for Traditional Sports of Minority
Nationalities which close here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China has a total of 56 nationalities. Besides the Hans, the
55 minority nationalities have about nine percent of the country's
total population of 1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
The quadrennial National Games and their local versions have
played an important role in promoting the economies of the hosting
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
In the southwestern province of Yunnan, for example, the six
provincial minority nationalities games held so far and the Fifth
National Games for Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities
staged in Kunming four years ago have greatly encouraged the local
enthusiasm in the construction of sports and infrastructure
facilities.
</P>
<P>
in 1995, Yunnan launched large-scale construction projects for
staging the fifth National Minorities Games in Kunming. Highways
were built to link Kunming and various tourist spots and seven
airports were constructed or re-built. When a new re-constructed
airport, Kunming became the fifth Chinese city with direct flights
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan's network of 10 airports now provides a much easier
transportation, which has thus greatly contributed to the success
of the on-going '99 World Gardening Fair Kunming.
</P>
<P>
Bao'an, a minority nationality in Gansu Province in the
northwest, is famed for the manufacture of various types of well-
decorated daggers, with the skills handed down through generations,
and popular game of "Dagger Chasing".
</P>
<P>
The game-turned sport has stimulated dagger production, which
has increased local people's incomes as well as tourist industry.
A village with large Bao'an community in the province has almost
all the families involved in dagger manufacturing, with one family
earning over 30,000 yuan RMB (3,700 U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
"Dagger manufacturing has now been one of the means for the Bao
'an people to get rich," said 38-year-old Ma Junfu, member of the
minority and one of Gansu's dagger chasers participating in the
Beijing Games.
</P>
<P>
The authorities of Longjing city in the Yanbian Korean
Autonomous Prefecture in northeastern Jilin Province had managed
to win the right to host the inaugural provincial games for
traditional sports for minority nationalities in 1991. They took
the games as a marketing chance for their rich sources of fruits
and a fruits festival right after the games attracted tourists and
businessmen from many other Chinese provinces and autonomous
regions. Their products are now well-known in China.
</P>
<P>
"The Games comes out a good marketing chance for us now," said
Li Xuexiu, an official of the Jilin provincial delegation at the
National Games in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
In Zhenyuan County of Qiandongnan Mao and Dong Autonomous
Prefecture in southwestern Chinese province of Guizhou, the annual
dragon boat races always attract teams and tourists from both
Guizhou and other provinces. With local hotels overbooked and
sales up, local residents enjoy an incomes rise at the occasion.
Local organizers plan to increase the scale of the dragon boat
races. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
