<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Gives Greater Security to Returnees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan migrant worker
returnees are to be provided greater security on arrival at the
Colombo International Airport, The Bureau of Foreign Employment
(BFE) here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Around 300 to 400 Sri Lankans, especially women workers,
return daily either on holiday or on the completion of their work
contracts abroad.
</P>
<P>
Many of them have fallen prey to unscrupulous taxi drivers and
touts on their return and have been waylaid and cheated and robbed
of their hard-earned money and other valuables on their way home
from the airport, the BFE sources said.
</P>
<P>
Henceforth these returnees will be provided maximum security on
arrival by law enforcement officers deployed by the Sri Lankan BFE
under a special program on a directive by President Chandrika
Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
They will be escorted from the tarmac to the BFE's Welfare
Center established at the airport and from there they will be
transported home in vehicles provided by the BFE.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1.2 million Sri Lankans working abroad and more
than 80 percent of them are female. Overseas remittance has been a
major source of revenue which helps sustain the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Overseas workers of Sri Lanka remitted back to the country over
880 million U.S. dollars last year. They already remitted 497
million dollars in the first half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
