<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Sets World Record: Singaporean Professor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A well-known Singaporean
Professor said China has created a world record in its economic
performance in the past decades, which is highlighted by its rapid
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, Professor John Wong,
research director of the East Asian Institute of the National
University of Singapore, said the performance of the Chinese
economy during the past two decades has been "singularly
spectacular with an annual growth rate of 9.8 percent, which is a
world record and twice the growth of India's economy."
</P>
<P>
Wong said China's total nominal GDP in 1978 was only 70 percent
that of South Korea. But by 1997 China's total GDP had become the
world's seventh largest and achieved parity in terms of purchasing
power, its economy was the world's second largest, following that
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said China's annual per capita GDP had increased 16 times
from 379 yuan in 1978 to 6,404 yuan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
China has clearly become an industrialized country, he said,
with only half of its labor force engaged in agricultural
activities and 85 percent of its total exports being manufactured
products.
</P>
<P>
It is still a little hard to believe that China can feed its 1.
25 billion population and even have a food surplus. It was
unthinkable a few years ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the first three decades of the PRC, China succeeded in
building a heavy industrial base.
</P>
<P>
After these past 20 years of reform, Chinese people are now
much better fed and better dressed as a result of income growth.
</P>
<P>
He added that Chinese people are also much freer to move about
to seek employment in the country and to travel or study abroad.
They have a totally different lifestyle from the previous decades.
</P>
<P>
He said the rise of the PRC is politically significant because
it is a new China that has risen from the ashes of century-long
foreign invasions and internal strife, a new China that has been
built on socialist principles, a new China that is under the
leadership of revolutionary and powerful leaders, and in a few
words, a new China that has finally stood up.
</P>
<P>
He concluded that Deng Xiaoping led China in a correct
direction and China's reform policy has been internationally
hailed as a great success.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the interview, Wong said that China is facing
some social problems in its economic progress, namely pollution,
traffic jams in cities, economic crimes and corruption.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that China make more effort to raise the
national education level, to alleviate the pollution problems, and
to speed up the progress of the rule of law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Growth Likely to Fall in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Credit growth in the Thai
banking system is expected to fall 1.4 percent year-on-year given
the low demand and some write-offs in problem loans, according to
a report of the Thai Farmers Research Center (TFRC) received
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The forecast comes just a day after Bangkok Bank, the country's
largest commercial bank, said that its loan growth target for 1999
at four percent may not be achievable and the bank is planning to
revise it down to two percent.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand, the central bank, forecast that loan
growth would reach four to eight percent this year, but is
expected to fall below the projection because most commercial
banks are still reluctant to resume lending to the real economic
sector fearing non-performing loans (NPLs) will increase.
</P>
<P>
The TFRC said in the report that the total loan amount this
year would reach 4.42 trillion baht (110.5 billion U.S. dollars).
However, the combined amount of deposits is expected to rise 4.2
percent to 4.54 trillion baht (113.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In addition, debt restructuring as well as problem loan
write-offs are likely to help reduce NPLs to 48 percent of total
loans from the current estimate of 51.3 percent by the year-end.
</P>
<P>
Thus loan-to-deposit ratio for 1999 would decline to 97.4
percent from 103.5 percent recorded in the middle of the year,
reflecting that liquidity in the money market remains ample.
</P>
<P>
The research house forecast that performing loans next year
would grow around 29.3 percent, pointing to the fact that the
country's economic recovery is expected to help raise fresh loan
extensions by 5.5 percent. An increase in restructured debts would
also help turn a certain amount of problem loans back into
performing ones once again.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the loan-to-deposit ratio next year
is expected to fall, ranging from 91.8 percent to 85 percent,
depending on how much of the problem loans would be written off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
