<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Criminal DNA Data Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 30 (Xinhua) -- DNA analysis has become an
important means of identifying people with criminal records in
China, and the country has got its first criminal DNA data bank in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The system was set up by the Justice Ministry's Judicial
Authentication Research Institute to store data on blood samples
of 2,500 criminals, according to official sources. With these
records, they can identify someone by analyzing a sample of hair
or a drop of blood, explains Shen Weizhong, director of the
institute.
</P>
<P>
He says that China plans to spend several 10 million yuan on
similar data banks, which will be connected to form a national
criminal DNA data bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., Britain, and Australia already have such data banks
using computer technology for DNA comparisons, with a high degree
of accuracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
