<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Number of Fossils Discovered in Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 29 (Xinhua)-- A large number of fossilized
remains of various animals have been discovered in recent years in
Fugu County, in the northern part of Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Many fossils found a decade ago were regarded by farmers as a
kind of medicine that they called "long gu" (dragon bones).
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, Chinese archeologists have studied 15 villages and
towns in the county for their abundance of fossils and have found
three layers of fossils, with more than 40 types of animal species
in the first, and 20 others like the three-toed horse and saber-
toothed cat in the second and third, which date back six or seven
million years.
</P>
<P>
Some scientists say that finding of so many fossilized remains
is rare. The mass of fossils has aroused the attention of local
officials, who established a fossil museum in 1996 and have
encouraged people to turn in fossils that they find.
</P>
<P>
The museum has two sets of rhinoceros skeletons and the
skeletons of a three-toed horse and giraffe are being restored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
