<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Use of Computerized Agriculture Increasing in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 30 (Xinhua) -- With just the click of a
mouse or the press of a key, Li Yushuang, a farmer in China's
Hebei Province can get information on irrigating his vegetables,
fertilization, and temperature, humidity, disease, and pest
control, as well as cost accounting and management techniques.
</P>
<P>
His father and grandfather used draft animals to cultivate
fields, but Li Yushuang is part of the modern generation of
farmers and his family is a microcosm of Chinese agricultural
development and the move from manual labor to computerized
management.
</P>
<P>
For decades, animals and the wooden and iron plough dominated
Chinese agriculture and slowed down its development. But, in
recent years, China has devoted itself to changing the old mode of
production and to mechanizing plowing, threshing, processing, and
irrigation.
</P>
<P>
In the old days, 3 mu (0.2 ha.) of land needed three or four
people to work it and output was very low, but now, one person can
do the job. Li's father got the first tractor in the village and
the machine saved time and labor, and other farmers soon did the
same. Old methods fade away, and in Li's town now, 82 percent of
the 280,000 families use tractors instead of animals.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Li spent 10,000 yuan on a computer and recently got on
the Internet. From that he got three new varieties of vegetables
and planting technology. As a result, his output has risen 10-fold.
</P>
<P>
Computer is now being widely used for information on irrigation,
crop planting, and breeding. The Ministry of Agriculture reports
that about 1 million farmers get on-line information these days on
cash crops and half a million get information on livestock and
poultry.
</P>
<P>
There are about 36.8 million people using machines for
agriculture in China's rural areas responding to the government's
call to create a service industry, and the rapid development of
agricultural production is expected to increase the modernization
of agriculture and industry, says Xu Fengxian of the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
China has 800 million farmers and is making an effort to reduce
the gap between developed parts of the country and underdeveloped
parts of the countryside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Remains Number One in Worldwide Fleet Tonnage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian merchant
fleet has registered shipping and freight carriers with weights
totaling 106 million tons so far this year, occupying the first
place among tonnage lists worldwide, said the Director of the
Panamanian Maritime Authority (AMP) Ruben Reyna on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, the Panamanian official said
that total tonnage of Panama's registered commercial fleet has
increased to 100 million tons presently from the level of 91
million tons registered in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The finance management office of the AMP collected 59.9 million
U.S. dollars in management charges last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Panama leads the world in the number of ships registered under
the Panamanian flag with over 6,000 units. It is closely followed
by Liberia, which has over 1,200 units flying its national flag.
</P>
<P>
The following countries, which have less than 1,000 units,
include Greece, Cyprus and the Bahamas, which occupy the third,
fourth and fifth places in the worldwide commercial fleet list.
</P>
<P>
Reyna also said that at present, Panama not only has the
highest registration of units in the world, but also the greatest
tonnage, which shows the preference of shipowners in obtaining
Panamanian registration.
</P>
<P>
Among the advantages gained by having a ship with a Panamanian
registration is that there are no restrictions as far as the
nationalities of the owners are concerned, lower taxes, and
greater anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Reyna said that Panama has transformed itself into a multi-
modal international maritime transport center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
