<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Veteran Witnesses to A Century of Modern Chinese History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The 94-year-old Liu Ying may
look just like any other old lady in the neighborhood with her
plain dress, but she is addressed as "Mother Liu" even by
President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Liu is the widow of the former Communist Party chief Zhang
Wentian, but is prominent in her own right with her legendary
experience. Liu is the oldest woman revolutionary in the Communist
Party of China. She survived the Long March of 1934 to 1935, where
the Communist Red Army trekked thousands of kilometers from
central China to the North to resist Kuomintang army attacks, as
well as numerous other struggles.
</P>
<P>
She devoted herself to student and labor movements when she was
only 20, then participated in the Long March, the War of
Resistance against Japanese Aggression (1937-1945), and the three-
year Civil War against the Kuomintang forces.
</P>
<P>
"I'll never forget the 'white terror' of the Kuomintang regime
in 1927," she recalls, "when the CPC lost the first civil war. So
many comrades and friends died." She still seems to feel the pain.
"But since then, their heroic deeds became my spiritual backing
that supports me in continuing revolutionary movements."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Liu's optimistic attitude towards life has helped her
through her ups and downs over the past half century, especially
during the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976), when she and her
husband suffered political persecution.
</P>
<P>
Now, sitting on a sofa, the silver-hair lady does not look war-
weary and is enjoying a restful life in Beijing. She does some
exercises for about half an hour in her backyard before breakfast
and plays with her great-grandchildren like most elderly Chinese
do.
</P>
<P>
At such an age, she is still concerned about national affairs
and says that the lesson that has been learned since the Opium War
is that a country will be trampled by others if it is not powerful
enough.
</P>
<P>
She missed the chance to attend the original celebrations for
the founding of the People's Republic in 1949 because she was
working in the Northeast, but, this year she is invited to watch
the parade past Tian'anmen Square for the country's 50th
anniversary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
