<HEADLINE> Colombia Rejects Foreign Intervention in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Colombian Vice-
President Gustavo Bell on Wednesday ruled out the possibility of
direct foreign intervention in Colombian government's peace talks
with the rebel Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC).
</P>
<P>
Bell, who arrived here Tuesday on a three-day visit, dismissed
such a possibility during a meeting with the Foreign Affairs
Commission of the Brazilian Chamber of Deputies.
</P>
<P>
He said the Colombian government of Andres Pastrana Arango
would restart negotiations with the FARC, the country's principal
guerrilla movement, next week to bring an end to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
However, Bell signaled that Colombia would accept cooperation
from North America or other countries willing to help in the fight
against drug trafficking. He maintained that this would not risk
Colombia's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Fabio Valencia, one of the government delegates in negotiations
with FARC, explained that the government-FARC talks were damaged
by drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Bell will travel to the largest Brazilian city of Sao Paulo
Thursday to meet with Brazilian businessmen. He will leave for
Lima Friday morning for a visit to Peru. 
</P>
