<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Athletics Face Drug Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- British athletics is facing
its biggest drugs crisis yet with the news that three unnamed
athletes have tested positive for banned substances, according to
local reports on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials at UK Athletics are keen to keep their disciplinary
proceedings under cover. They will only make public the names of
those athletes who have been found guilty.
</P>
<P>
However, figures released by UK Sport's anti-doping agency
showed there were three unknown cases in the pending tray of the
British governing body.
</P>
<P>
"UK Athletics feels very strongly that confidentiality should
be respected. The individual should be protected until the facts
have been considered," said UK Athletics spokeswoman Jayne Pearce.
</P>
<P>
"We have made our position clear on this and we are sad that
our procedures have again not been taken into account by a third
party."
</P>
<P>
The anabolic steroid nandrolone is again among the banned
substances found, creating further headaches for officials at UK
Athletics' Birmingham headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Linford Christie, Doug Walker and hurdler Gary Cadogan all
tested positive for a nandrolone metabolite but saw their cases
dismissed by UK Athletics' panel of medical and scientific experts.
</P>
<P>
All three cases are now with the International Amateur
Athletics Federation and the world governing body have the power
to overturn their acquittal and impose a two-year ban.
</P>
<P>
The athlete who tested positive for nandrolone is currently
having his or her case reviewed and may be required to appear
before a disciplinary committee at a later date.
</P>
<P>
Another athlete's out-of-competition sample showed traces of
stanozol, the anabolic steroid found in Ben Johnson's urine sample
at the 1988 Olympic Games in Seoul. That case is also due before a
team of British experts in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
