<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Chinese in New Zealand Celebrate China's National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Overseas Chinese in New
Zealand have been organizing various activities in celebration of
the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of
China as the New China's birthday, October 1, is approaching.
</P>
<P>
During the past few days, they have held theatrical
performances, photo exhibitions, lectures and other activities to
praise New China's tremendous achievements in both political and
economic fields over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
In Auckland, the biggest city of New Zealand, seven overseas
Chinese organizations held a theatrical performance with more than
3,000 people attending, which was unprecedented in scale.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Transport Minister Maurice Williamson spoke at the
gathering on behalf of Prime Minister Jenny Shipley. While
extending his warm congratulations to the Chinese people on the
occasion of the 50th anniversary of the founding of the PRC,
Williamson said that Chinese President Jiang Zemin's recent visit
to New Zealand has greatly enhanced New Zealand-China relations.
He also highly appreciated the outstanding contributions made by
the overseas Chinese in New Zealand to the formation of a
multiculture New Zealand society.
</P>
<P>
At the gathering, Chinese Consul-General to Auckland Wu Zuqiu
extended festive greetings to the local overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Local overseas Chinese and New Zealand artists, and artists
from Beijing, who made a special trip to Auckland, presented a
rich variety of performances, which won warm applause from the
audience.
</P>
<P>
Former New Zealand governor-general Paul Reeves and his wife,
and local senior government officials attended the gathering.
</P>
<P>
A photo exhibition on New China's achievements over the past 50
years was also held at the place for the theatrical performance.
</P>
<P>
In Wellington, capital of New Zealand, four major overseas
Chinese organizations celebrated China's National Day by jointly
giving a banquet. Nearly 200 local overseas Chinese and New
Zealanders were present on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the four sponsors, Vice-President of the
Wellington Branch of the New Zealand Chinese Association Ester
Fung said in her toast that the 20th century has been "a momentous
one for China" and "China has grown from being lowly regarded as a
country to being a power of great significance".
</P>
<P>
She noted that politically China is recognized as a great power
and economically China has made great strides with an economy
which can "greatly influence not only countries near her in the
Pacific region but also globally".
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador Chen Wenzhao thanked overseas Chinese for
their valuable contributions to the motherland's development. He
stressed that every achievement the Chinese people have made is
linked with the concern and efforts of the overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Chen said that Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
recent successful visit to New Zealand has laid a solid foundation
for further growth of Sino-New Zealand ties. He encouraged the
overseas Chinese in New Zealand to do more in strengthening the
bilateral relations between China and New Zealand and making
greater efforts for the prosperity of China.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington Branch of the New Zealand-China Friendship
Society, which has for decades been working for promoting
people-to-people contacts between the two countries, has organized
lectures, film shows, and a reception, marking New China's
birthday.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua Chinese Language School in Wellington also gathered
to celebrate New China's golden jubilee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
