<DOCNO> XIE19990930.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United, Lazio, Barcelona and Arsenal Stay Unbeaten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Two late goals from Andy Cole
and Paul Scholes helped Manchester United of England defeat
Olympique Marseille of France 2-1 in the Champions League on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Also in the day's games, Lazio, who have designs on United's
title, had no such troubles, crushing Maribor Teatanic 4-0 in Rome.
</P>
<P>
Barcelona, another club eyeing the title, failed to see off
another likely contender, Arsenal, in the Nou Camp. They drew 1-1,
with Arsenal finding a late equaliser after being reduced to 10
men.
</P>
<P>
All four remain unbeaten at the halfway stage of the opening
group games.
</P>
<P>
But Austrians Sturm Graz suffered third consecutive defeat on
Wednesday when they were crushed 3-0 by Croatia Zagreb, which
meant they were all but eliminated.
</P>
<P>
United's late show at a rain-lashed Old Trafford was not quite
as heart-stopping as their 2-1 victory over Bayern Munich when
they scored twice in the last 90 seconds to win that final last
season-- but they still came late enough for United to be staring
defeat in the face.
</P>
<P>
Marseille, who had gone ahead through Ibrahima Bakayoko after
41 minutes held that lead until the 79th minute when Andy Cole
equalised with a spectacular left-footed overhead bicycle kick.
The winner came seven minutes from time when Paul Scholes hooked
the ball home from close range.
</P>
<P>
A relieved United manager Alex Ferguson, who saw his team
extend their unbeaten run in all competitive matches to 45,said: "
I don't think we played quite as well in the second half as we did
in the first half, funnily enough.
</P>
<P>
"But Cole's goal -- that was something special."
</P>
<P>
The victory took United to the top of group D, a point clear of
Marseille.
</P>
<P>
In the same group, Croatia Zagreb, who were beaten 2-1 at home
by Marseille last week, revived their chances of a place in the
second round with a 3-0 win over Sturm Graz.
</P>
<P>
Tomislav Rukavina (27) and Tomislav Sokota (34 and 58 pen)
scored to move Zagreb on to four points.
</P>
<P>
Lazio, who beat Manchester United 1-0 to win the UEFA Super Cup
-- classed as a friendly -- a month ago in Monte Carlo,underlined
their threat to United's crown by moving clear at the top of group
A with a 4-0 win over Maribor Teatanic.
</P>
<P>
The Slovenian champions were reduced to 10 men after 20 minutes
when defender Geri Cipi was sent off for a bad tackle --although
it took Lazio 40 minutes to break down their stubborn resistance.
</P>
<P>
Then the floodgates opened with four goals in 15 minutes with
Simone Inzaghi (60) Sergio Conceicao (62) and two from Marcelo
Salas (71 and 75) wrapping up the points with a great volley for
his second.
</P>
<P>
Bayer Leverkusen, previous group A leaders, slipped to second
after they were held 1-1 at home by Dynamo Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Lazio head the group with seven points, two clear of Leverkusen
(5), who are followed by Maribor (3) and Kiev (1).
</P>
<P>
Barcelona, another club with designs on the title, remained top
of group B despite their failure to see off an Arsenal side
reduced to 10 men in the closing stages at the Nou Camp.
</P>
<P>
The match ended 1-1 after Luis Enrique Martinez gave Barcelona
a 16th minute lead following some dreadful defending by goalkeeper
Alex Manninger and Patrick Vieira.
</P>
<P>
The London side equalised nine minutes from time when Nigerian
international Nwankwo Kanu struck with typical opportunism after a
Davor Suker shot had been parried.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal finished a player short after defender Gilles Grimandi
was sent off 12 minutes from time for elbowing.
</P>
<P>
It was Arsenal's first red card of the season but their 22nd
since Arsene Wenger became manager three years ago.
</P>
<P>
AIK Stockholm and Fiorentina drew 0-0 in the other group B
match, leaving Barcelona top with seven points followed by Arsenal
on five, Fiorentina (2) and AIK (1).
</P>
<P>
There was a thrilling group C tie in Trondheim where Rosenborg
fought back from 2-0 down to draw 2-2 with Borussia Dortmund, who
had raced into an early lead through Sergei Barbarez (11) and
Juergen Kohler (22).
</P>
<P>
But the Norwegians recovered with goals from Jan Derek Sorensen
(35) and teenager John Carew (68), who enhanced his growing
reputation even further with his third goal of the competition.
</P>
<P>
In the other group C match, Boavista goalkeeper William Bassey
Andem was sent off a minute from time against Feyenoord,soon after
Mario Silva saved a point for his side with an 86th minute
equaliser. Paul Bosvlet had put Feyenoord ahead in the 62nd minute.
</P>
<P>
Borussia and Rosenborg have five points, Feyenoord three and
Boavista one.
</P>
<P>
After three weeks of relentless action, the Champions League
will have a break until October 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
